<DIV1 TYPE="play">
<PB REF="7">
<HEAD>FALSE DELICACY.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I. SCENE I.</HEAD>
<P><HI>An Apartment at</HI> Lady BETTY LAMBTON'S.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SIDNEY <HI>and</HI> WINWORTH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>STILL I can't help thinking but Lady Betty Lambton's refu&s;al was infinitely more the re&s;ult of an extraordinary delicacy, than the want of affection for your Lord&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>O my dear cou&s;in you are very much mi&s;taken; I am not one of tho&s;e coxcombs who imagine a woman does'nt know her own mind, or who, be|cau&s;e they are treated with civility by a lady who has rejected their addre&s;&s;es, &s;uppo&s;e &s;he is &s;ecretly debating in their favour: Lady Betty is a woman of &s;en&s;e, and mu&s;t con&s;equently de&s;pi&s;e coquetry or affectation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;he always &s;peaks of you with the greate&s;t re&s;pect.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="2" REF="8">
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Re&s;pect! &mdash; Why &s;he always &s;peaks of you with the greate&s;t re&s;pect; does it therefore follow that &s;he loves you? No Charles &mdash; I have, for &s;ome time you know, ceas'd to trouble Lady Betty with my &s;olicitations, and I &s;ee my&s;elf honour'd with her friend&s;hip, though I hav'nt been &s;o hap|py as to merit her heart; for this rea&s;on I have no doubt of her a&s;&s;i&s;tance on the pre&s;ent occa&s;ion, and I am certain I &s;hall plea&s;e her by making my addre&s;&s;es to Mi&s;s Marchmont.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Marchmont is indeed a very de&s;erving young woman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Next to Lady Betty I never &s;aw one &s;o form'd to my wi&s;hes; be&s;ides, during the whole period of my fruitle&s;s attendance, &s;he &s;eemed &s;o intere&s;ted for my &s;ucce&s;s, and expre&s;s'd &s;o hearty a concern for my di&s;appointment, that I have con&s;ider'd her with an eye of more than common friend&s;hip ever &s;ince. &mdash; But what's the matter with you Charles, you &s;eem to have &s;omething upon your &s;pirits?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed my Lord you are mi&s;taken, I am only attentive.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, is that all! &mdash; This very day I purpo&s;e to reque&s;t Lady Betty's intere&s;t with Mi&s;s March|mont, for unhappily circum&s;tanc'd as &s;he is, with regard to fortune, &s;he po&s;&s;e&s;&s;es an uncommon &s;hare of delicacy, and may po&s;&s;ibly think her&s;elf
<PB N="3" REF="9">in&s;ulted by the offer of a rejected heart; &mdash; Lady Betty in that ca&s;e will &s;ave her the pain of a &s;uppo&s;ed di&s;re&s;pect, and me the mortification of a new repul&s;e. But I beg your pardon, Charles, I am forgetting the cau&s;e of friend&s;hip, and &s;hall now &s;tep up &s;tairs to Colonel Rivers about your affair. &mdash; Ah Sidney you have no difficulties to ob&s;truct the completion of your wi&s;hes, and a few days mu&s;t make you one of the happi&s;t men in England.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[looking after him.]</STAGE>
<P>A few days make me one of the happie&s;t men in England, &mdash; a likely matter truly; little does he know how I pa&s;&s;ionately admire the very wo|man to whom he is immediately going with an offer of his per&s;on and fortune. &mdash; The marriage with Mi&s;s Rivers I &s;ee is unavoidable, and I am almo&s;t plea&s;ed that I never obtained any encou|ragement from Mi&s;s Marchmont, as I &s;hould now be reduc'd to the painful alternative, either of giving up my own hopes, or of oppo&s;ing the happine&s;s of &s;uch a friend.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Mrs. HARLEY <HI>and</HI> Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>O here my dear girl is the &s;weet &s;wain in <HI>pro|pria per&s;ona:</HI> &mdash; Only mind what a funeral &s;ermon|face the creature has, notwith&s;tanding the agree|able pro&s;pects before him. &mdash; Well of all things in the world defend me I &s;ay from a &s;ober hu&s;band!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are extreamly welcome Mrs. Harley to divert your&s;elf&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="4" REF="10">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>He &s;peaks too in as melancholy a tone as a pa&s;&s;ing bell: &mdash; Lord, lord, what can Colonel Rivers &s;ee in the wretch to think of him for a &s;on-in-law. &mdash; Only look Mi&s;s Marchmont at this love-exciting countenance; &mdash; Ob&s;erve the Cu|pids that ambu&s;h in the&s;e eyes; &mdash; The&s;e lips to be &s;ure are fraught with the honey of Hybla: &mdash; Go you lifele&s;s devil you, &mdash; go try to get a little animation into this unfortunate face of yours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my word my face is very much oblig'd to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are a mad creature, my dear, and yet I envy your &s;pirits prodigiou&s;ly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o you ought. &mdash; But for all that you and Lady Betty are unaccountably fond of tho&s;e half-&s;oul'd fellows, who are as mechanically regular as &s;o many pieces of clock-work, and never &s;trike above once an hour upon a new ob&s;ervation &mdash; who are &s;o &s;entimental, and &s;o dull &mdash; &s;o wi&s;e and &s;o drow&s;y. &mdash; Why I thought Lady Betty had al|ready a &s;ufficient quantity of lead in her family without taking in this lump to increa&s;e the weight of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>What can &s;he po&s;ibly mean, Mr. Sidney.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis impo&s;&s;ible to gue&s;s madam. The lively widow will &s;till have her laugh without &s;paring any body.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="5" REF="11">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;urely, my dear, you can't forget the coun|ter part of poor di&s;mal here, that elaborate piece of dignified dulne&s;s, Lady Betty's cou&s;in Lord Hectic; who through downright fondne&s;s is con|tinually plaguing his poor wife, and rendering her the mo&s;t mi&s;erable woman in the world, from an extraordinary de&s;ire of promoting her happi|ne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>And is'nt there a great deal to &s;ay in exte|nuation of an error which proceeds from a prin|ciple of real affection?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Affection! ridiculous! but you &s;hall have an in&s;tance of this wonderful affection: &mdash; T'other day I din'd at his hou&s;e, and, though the wea|ther was intollerably warm, the table was laid in a clo&s;e room, with a fire large enough to roa&s;t an ox for a country corporation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, and &s;o &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>In a great chair, near the fire &s;ide, &s;at poor Lady Hectic, wrapp'd up in as many fur cloaks as would ba&s;&s;le the &s;everity of a winter in Sibe|ria: &mdash;On my entrance I expre&s;s'd a proper con|cern for her illne&s;s, and a&s;k'd the nature of her complaint. &mdash; She told me &s;he complain'd of no|thing but the weight of her dre&s;s, and the in|tollerable heat of the apartment; adding, that &s;he had been caught in a little &s;hower the pre|ceding
<PB N="6" REF="12">evening, which terri&s;ied Lord Hectic out of his wits, and &s;o for fear &s;he might run the chance of a &s;light cold, he expo&s;ed her to the hazard of ab&s;olute &s;uffocation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my word, Mi&s;s Marchmont, &s;he has a pretty manner of turning things.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Really I think &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well &mdash; unable to bear either the tyranny of this prepo&s;terous fondne&s;s any longer, or the intollerable heat of his room, I made my e&s;cape the moment the cloth was removed, and &s;han't be &s;urpri&s;ed if before the conclu&s;ion of the &s;ummer, he is brought before his peers for having murdered his poor lady out of downright affection.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>A very uncommon death, Mrs. Harley, among people of quality.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter a</HI> FOOTMAN.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FOOTMAN <HI>to</HI> SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord Winworth, Sir, de&s;ires the favour of your company above: the per&s;on is come with the writings from the Temple&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll wait upon him immediately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="7" REF="13">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay pray do, you are the fitte&s;t company in the world for each other. &mdash; If Colonel Rivers was of my mind he'd turn you in&s;tantly adrift and li&s;ten to the overtures of Sir Harry Newburg.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I really believe you have a fancy to me your|&s;elf, you're &s;o con&s;tantly abu&s;ing me.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I, you odious creature!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now you mention Sir Harry, my dear, is'nt it rather extraordinary for him to think about Mi&s;s Rivers, when he knows of the engagements between her and Mr. Sidney &mdash; e&s;pecially as her father has &s;uch an objection to the wildne&s;s of his character.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>What you are &s;till at your &s;ober reflections I &s;ee, and are for &s;crutinizing into the morals of a lover.&mdash;The women truly would have a fine time of it if they were never to be married till they found men of unexceptionable characters.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay I don't want to le&s;&s;en Sir Harry's merit in the lea&s;t, &mdash; he has his good qualities as well as his faults &mdash; and is no way de&s;titute of under|&s;tanding &mdash; but &s;till his under&s;tanding is a fa&s;hi|onable one, and pleads the knowledge of every thing right, to ju&s;tify the practice of many things not &s;trictly warrantable.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="8" REF="14">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why I never heard any thing to his prejudice but &s;ome fa&s;hionable liberties which he has taken with the ladies.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>And in the name of wonder what wou'd you de&s;ire to hear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come, Horten&s;ia, we women are unac|countable creatures, the greate&s;t number of us by much love a fellow for having a little modi&s;h wildne&s;s about him, and if we are &s;uch fools as to be captivated with the vices of the men, we ought to be puni&s;hed for the depravity of our &s;entiments.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RIVERS <HI>and</HI> Lady BETTY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you &s;i&s;ter they can read the parchments very well without our a&s;&s;i&s;tance &mdash; and I have been &s;o fatigu'd with looking over papers all the morning, that I am heartily &s;ick of your Indentures, witne&s;&s;ing, your fora&s;much's, likewi&s;e's al&s;o's, moreover's and notwith&s;tanding's, and I mu&s;t take a turn in the garden to recover my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay I only &s;poke becau&s;e I imagin'd our being pre&s;ent would be more agreeable to Lord Win|worth. &mdash; But I wonder Sir Harry does'nt come, he promi&s;ed to be here by ten, and I want to &s;ee his cou&s;in Cecil mightily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="9" REF="15">
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, Lady Betty, does Mr. Cecil come with him here this morning?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>He does, my dear &mdash; he arrived at Sir Harry's la&s;t night, and I want to &s;ee if his late journey to France has any way improved the elegance of his appearance.</P>
<STAGE>[ironically.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I &s;hall be glad to &s;ee him too; for, not|with&s;tanding his di&s;regard of dre&s;s, and freedom of manner &mdash; there is a &s;omething right in him that plea&s;es me prodigiou&s;ly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;omething right, Mrs. Harley! &mdash; he is one of the worthie&s;t creatures in the world.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, Horten&s;ia, he ought to be a favourite of yours, for I don't know any body who po&s;&s;e&s;&s;es a higher place in his good opinion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Twou'd be odd, indeed, if he was'nt a fa|vourite of mine &mdash; he was my father's be&s;t friend; &mdash; gave him a con&s;iderable living you know, and, when he died, wou'd have provided very kindly for me, if your genero&s;ity, Lady Betty, had'nt render'd his goodne&s;s wholly unnece&s;&s;ary.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pooh! Pooh! no more of this.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> wi&s;h there was a po&s;&s;ibility of making him dre&s;s like a gentleman &mdash; But I am glad he comes
<PB N="10" REF="16">with Sir Harry; &mdash; for though they have a great regard for each other, they are continually wrang|ling, and form a contra&s;t which is often extremely diverting &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter a Footman.</STAGE>
<SP>
<P>Sir Harry Newburg and Mr. Cecil, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, here they are! Shew them in.</P>
<STAGE>Exit Footm.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now for it!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h, they are here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ladies your mo&s;t obedient. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Girls! &mdash; give me a ki&s;s each of you in|&s;tantly. &mdash; Lady Betty, I am heartily glad to &s;ee you: &mdash; I have a budget full of compliments for you, from &s;everal of your friends at Paris &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did you meet any of them at Paris?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I did, &mdash; and, what was wor&s;e, I met them in every town I pa&s;&s;ed through; &mdash; but the Engli&s;h are a great commercial nation, you know, and their fools like their broad cloths, are exported in large quantities to all parts of Europe.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="11" REF="17">
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>What? and they found you a fool &s;o much above the market price, that they have returned you upon the hands of your country? &mdash; Here, ladies, is a head for you, piping hot from Paris.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>And here, ladies, is a head for you, like the Alps.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Like the Alps, ladies! How do you make that out?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why it's always white, and always barren; 'tis con&s;tantly covered with &s;now, but never pro|duces any thing profitable.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>O &s;ay no more upon that head, I be&s;eech you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, Sir Harry, I think they're too hard for you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, I think &s;o too &mdash; e&s;pecially my friend Cecil, who, with that unfortunate &s;hock of hair, has no great right to be con&s;idered as a &s;tandard for dre&s;s in this country.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, widow, there are many heads in this coun|try with much more extraordinary things upon them than my unfortunate &s;hock of hair, as you call it: &mdash; what do you think of the&s;e wings, for in&s;tance, that cover the ears of my cou&s;in Mer|cury?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="12" REF="18">
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Death! don't &s;poil my hair.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;ee this fellow is &s;o tortur'd upon the wheel of fa&s;hion, that a &s;ingle touch immediately throws him into agonies; &mdash; now, my dre&s;s is as ea&s;y as it's &s;imple, and five minutes &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>With the help of your five fingers equips you at any time for the drawing-room, &mdash; ha! ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>And is'nt it better than being five hours under the paws of your hair-dre&s;&s;er?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>But cu&s;tom, Mr. Cecil! &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Men of &s;en&s;e have nothing to do with cu&s;tom, and 'tis more their bu&s;ine&s;s to &s;et wi&s;e examples than to follow fooli&s;h ones.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>But don't you think the world will be apt to laugh a little, Mr. Cecil?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can't help the want of under&s;tanding among mankind.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>The blockhead thinks there's nothing due to the general opinion of one's country.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>And none but blockheads like you would mind the fooli&s;h opinions of any country.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="13" REF="19">
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well! Mr. Cecil mu&s;t take his own way, I think &mdash; &s;o come along, ladies, &mdash; let us go into the ga<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">den, and &s;end my brother to Sir Harry to &s;ettle the bu&s;ine&s;s about Theodora.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Theodora! &mdash; what a charming name for the romance of a circulating library. &mdash; I wonder, Lady Betty, your brother wou'd'nt call his girl Deborah, after her grandmother &mdash;?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARRLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Deborah! &mdash; O I &s;hould hate &s;uch an old fa|&s;hioned name abominably &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I hate this new fa&s;hion of calling our children by pompous appellations. &mdash; By and by we &s;han't have a Ralph or a Roger, a Bridget or an Alice remaining in the kingdom. &mdash; The dregs of the people have adopted this unaccount|able cu&s;tom, and a fellow who keeps a little ale|hou&s;e at the bottom of my avenue in the country, has no le&s;s than an Augu&s;tus-Frederick, a Scipio Africanus, and a Matilda-Wilhelmina-Leonora, in his family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my word, a very pretty &s;tring of chri&s;|tian names.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Sir Harry, you and Mr. Cecil dine with us. &mdash; Come, ladies, let us go to the garden.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I po&s;itively won't go without Mr. Cecil, for I mu&s;t have &s;omebody to laugh at.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="14" REF="20">
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o mu&s;t I, widow, therefore I won't lo&s;e this opportunity of being in your company.</P>
<STAGE>[<HI>Exeunt ladies and followed by</HI> CECIL, <HI>who meets</HI> RIVERS <HI>entering.</HI>]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Colonel, I am heartily glad to &s;ee you. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Cecil, you are welcome home again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's my wi&s;e kin&s;man wants a word with you.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Colonel, your mo&s;t obedient: &mdash; I am come upon the old bu&s;ine&s;s; &mdash;for unle&s;s I am allow'd to entertain hope of Mi&s;s Rivers, I &s;hall be the mo&s;t mi&s;erable of human beings.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Harry, I have already told you by letter, and I now tell you per&s;onally, I cannot li&s;ten to your propo&s;als.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir, &mdash; I have promi&s;ed my daughter to Mr. Sidney; &mdash; do you know that, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do; &mdash; but what then? Engagements of this kind, you know &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>So then, you do know I have promi&s;ed her to Mr. Sidney?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="15" REF="21">
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do; &mdash; but I al&s;o know that matters are not finally &s;ettled between Mr. Sidney and you, and I moreover know, that his fortune is by no means equal to mine, therefore &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Harry, let me a&s;k you one que&s;tion before you make your con&s;equence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>A thou&s;and if you plea&s;e, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then, Sir, let me a&s;k you, what you have ever ob&s;erved in me or my conduct, that you de|&s;ire me &s;o familiarly to break my word: &mdash; I thought, Sir, you con&s;idered me as a man of honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o I do, Sir, a man of the nice&s;t honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>And yet, Sir, you a&s;k me to violate the &s;anctity of my word &mdash; and tell me indirectly that it is my intere&s;t to be a ra&s;cal &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I really don't under&s;tand you, Colonel: &mdash; I thought, when I was talking to you I was talk|ing to a man who knew the world &mdash; and as you have not yet &s;igned &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, this is mending matters with a witne&s;s! &mdash; And &s;o you think becau&s;e I am not legally bound, I am under no nece&s;&s;ity of keeping my word! &mdash; Sir Harry, laws were never made for men of honour; &mdash; they want no bond but the
<PB N="16" REF="22">rectitude of their own &s;entiments, and laws are of no u&s;e but to bind the villains of &s;ociety.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well! but my dear Colonel, if you have no regard for me, &s;hew &s;ome little regard for your daughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Harry, I &s;hew the greate&s;t regard for my daughter by giving her to a man of honour; &mdash; and I mu&s;t not be in&s;ulted with any farther repetition of your propo&s;als.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>In&s;ult you Colonel! &mdash; is the offer of my al|liance an in&s;ult? &mdash; is my readine&s;s to make what &s;ettlements you think proper &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Harry, I &s;hould con&s;ider the offer of a kingdom an in&s;ult, if it was to be purcha&s;ed by the violation of my word: &mdash; Be&s;ides, though my daughter &s;hall never go a beggar to the arms of her hu&s;band, I wou'd rather &s;ee her happy than rich; and if &s;he has enough to provide hand&s;ome|ly for a young family, and &s;omething to &s;pare for the exigencies of a worthy friend, I &s;hall think her as affluent as if &s;he was mi&s;tre&s;s of Mexico.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Colonel, I have done; &mdash; but I believe &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Sir Harry, and as our conference is done, we will, if you plea&s;e, retire to the ladies: &mdash; I &s;hall be always glad of your acquaintance though I can't receive you as a &s;on-in-law, &mdash; for a union of intere&s;t I look upon as a union of di&s;honour, and con&s;ider a marriage for money, at be&s;t, but a legal pro&s;titution.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.]</STAGE>
<TRAILER><HI>End of the fir&s;t</HI> ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<PB N="17" REF="23">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE <HI>a Garden.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Lady BETTY, <HI>and</HI> Mrs. HARLEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>LORD, Lord, my dear you're enough to drive one out of one's wits. &mdash; I tell you, again and again, he's as much yours as ever; and was I in your &s;ituation, he &s;hou'd be my hu&s;band to-morrow morning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Emmy you mi&s;take the matter &s;trangely. &mdash; Lord Winworth is no common man, nor wou'd he have continued his &s;ilence &s;o long upon his favourite &s;ubject, if he had the lea&s;t inclination to renew his addre&s;&s;es. &mdash; His pride has ju&s;tly taken the alarm at my in&s;en&s;ibility, and he will not, I am &s;atisfied, run the hazard of another refu&s;al.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then, in the name of wonder, if he was &s;o dear to you, cou'd you prodigally trifle with your own happine&s;s, and repeatedly refu&s;e him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have repeatedly told you becau&s;e I was a fool, Emmy. &mdash; Till he withdrew his addre&s;&s;es I knew not how much I e&s;teemed him; my unhappine&s;s in my fir&s;t marriage, you know, made me re&s;olve again&s;t another. &mdash; And you are al&s;o &s;en&s;ible I have frequently argued that a woman of real de|licacy &s;hou'd never admit a &s;econd impre&s;&s;ion on her heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="18" REF="24">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, and I always thought you argued very fooli&s;hly. &mdash; I am &s;ure I ought to know, for I have been twice married; &mdash; and though I lov'd my fir&s;t hu&s;band very &s;incerely, there was not a woman in England who cou'd have made the &s;econd a better wife. &mdash; Nay, for that matter, if another was to offer him&s;elf to-morrow, I am not altogether certain that I &s;hould refu&s;e li&s;tening &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are a &s;trange creature.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>And are'nt you a much &s;tranger, in declining to follow your own inclinations, when you cou'd have con&s;ulted them &s;o highly, to the credit of your good &s;en&s;e, and the &s;atisfaction of your whole family. &mdash; But it is'nt yet too late; and if you will be advi&s;ed by me every thing &s;hall end as happily as you can wi&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, let me hear your advice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why this, then: &mdash; My Lord you know has reque&s;ted that you wou'd indulge him with half an hour's private conver&s;ation &s;ome time this morning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is a liberty he has'nt taken the&s;e three months &mdash; and he mu&s;t de&s;ign &s;omething by it; &mdash; now as he can de&s;ign nothing but to renew his addre&s;&s;es, I wou'd advi&s;e you to take
<PB N="19" REF="25">him at the very fir&s;t word, for fear your delicacy, if it has time to con&s;ider, &s;hou'd again &s;hew you the &s;trange impropriety of &s;econd marriages.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;uppo&s;e this &s;hould not be his bu&s;ine&s;s with me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then we'll go another way to work: &mdash; I, as a &s;anguine friend of my Lord's, can give him a di&s;tant hint of matters, exacting at the &s;ame time a promi&s;e of the mo&s;t inviolable &s;ecrecy; and a&s;&s;uring him you wou'd never forgive me, if you had the lea&s;t idea of my having acquainted him with &s;o important a &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o you wou'd have me &mdash;?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why not? &mdash; This is the very &s;tep I &s;hou'd take my&s;elf, if I was in your &s;ituation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>May be &s;o: &mdash; But it's a &s;tep which I &s;hall never take. &mdash; What! wou'd you have me lo&s;t to all feeling? Wou'd you have me meanly make u&s;e of chambermaid artifices for a hu&s;band?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY:</SPEAKER>
<P>I would only have you happy my dear: &mdash; And where the man of one's heart is at &s;take I don't think we ought to &s;tand &s;o rigidly upon trifles. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Trifles, Emmy! do you call the laws of de|licacy trifles. &mdash; She that violates the&s;e &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="20" REF="26">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poh! poh! &s;he that violates: &mdash; What a work there is with you &s;entimental folks. &mdash; Why, don't I tell you that my Lord &s;hall never know any thing of your concern in the de&s;ign?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;ha'nt I know it my&s;elf, Emmy! &mdash; and how can I e&s;cape the ju&s;tice of my own reflections!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, thank heav'n my &s;entiments are not &s;uf|ficiently refin'd to make me unhappy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can't change my &s;entiments, my dear Emmy, &mdash; nor wou'd I, if I cou'd: &mdash; Of this, however, be certain, that unle&s;s I have Lord Winworth without courting him, I &s;hall never have him at all. &mdash; But be &s;ilent to all the world upon this matter I conjure you: &mdash; Particularly to Mi&s;s Marchmont; for &s;he has been &s;o &s;trenuous an advocate for my Lord, that the concealment of it from her might give her &s;ome doubts of my friend&s;hip; and I &s;hou'd be continually unea&s;y for fear my re&s;erve &s;hou'd be con&s;ider'd as an indirect in&s;ult upon her circum&s;tances.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, the devil take this delicacy; I don't know any thing it does be&s;ides making people mi&s;erable: &mdash; And yet &s;ome how, fooli&s;h as it is, one can't help liking it. &mdash; But yonder I &s;ee Sir Harry and Mr. Cecil.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let us withdraw then my dear; they may de|tain us; and, 'till this interview is over, I &s;hall
<PB N="21" REF="27">be in a continual agitation; yet I am &s;trangely apprehen&s;ive of a di&s;appointment, Emmy &mdash; and if &mdash;</P>
<STAGE>[going]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY</SPEAKER>
<P>Lady Betty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do you &s;ay?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you &s;till think there is any thing extremely prepo&s;terous in &s;econd marriages?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are intolerably provoking. &mdash;</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> CECIL <HI>and</HI> Sir HARRY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, did'nt I tell you the moment you opened this affair to me, that the Colonel was a man of too much &s;en&s;e to give his daughter to a cox|comb?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>But what if I &s;hould tell you, that his daugh|ter &s;hall be &s;till mine, and in &s;pite of his teeth?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Prithee explain kin&s;man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;uppo&s;e Mi&s;s Rivers &s;hould have no very &s;trong objection to this unfortunate figure of mine?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why even your vanity can't think that a young lady of her good &s;en&s;e, can po&s;&s;ibly be in love with you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="22" REF="28">
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, you think that no likely circum&s;tance I &s;ee?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do really &mdash; Formerly indeed the women were fools enough to be caught by the frippery of externals, and &s;o a fellow neither picked a pocket, nor put up with an affront, he was a dear toad &mdash; a &s;weet creature &mdash; and a wicked devil; &mdash; nay the wicked devil, was quite an an|gel of a man &mdash; and like another Alexander, in proportion to the number of wretches which he made, he con&s;tantly increa&s;ed the lu&s;tre of his reputation &mdash; till at la&s;t, having conquered all his worlds, he &s;at down with that celebrated ruffian, and wept becau&s;e he cou'd commit no farther outrages upon &s;ociety.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>O my good moralizing cou&s;in, you'll find your &s;elf cur&s;edly out in your politics; and I &s;hall convince you in a few hours, that a hand&s;ome &s;uit on the back of a &s;prightly young fellow, will &s;till do more among the women, than all your &s;entiment and &s;lovenline&s;s. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>What wou'd you per&s;uade me that Mi&s;s Rivers will go off with you &mdash;?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have hit the mark for once in your life, my &s;weet temper'd mouther of morality &mdash; The dear Theodora &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>The dear Theodora! and &s;o Harry you ima|gine that by the common maxims of fa&s;hionable
<PB N="23" REF="29">life, you may appear to be a friend to the Colo|nel at the very moment you are going to rob him of his daughter. &mdash; For &s;hame kin&s;man &mdash; for &s;hame &mdash; have &s;ome pride if you have no virtue &mdash; and dont &s;mile in a man's face when you want to do him the greate&s;t of all injuries &mdash; dont Harry &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cecil I &s;corn a ba&s;e action as much as you or as much as any man &mdash; but I love Mi&s;s Rivers honourably. &mdash; I a&s;k nothing from her father, and as her per&s;on is her own &s;he has a right to be|&s;tow it where &s;he plea&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am an&s;wered &mdash; her per&s;on is her own &mdash; and &s;he has a right to be mi&s;erable her own way. &mdash; I acknowledge it &mdash; and will not di&s;cover your &s;ecret to her father. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Di&s;cover it to her father &mdash; why &s;ure you woud'nt think of it. &mdash; Take care Cecil &mdash; take care &mdash; I do indeed love you better than any man in the world &mdash; and I know you have a friend&s;hip, a cordial friend&s;hip for me &mdash; but the happine&s;s of my whole life is at &s;take, and mu&s;t not be de|&s;troyed by any of your unaccountable peculiarities.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Harry &mdash; you know I wou'd at any time rather promote your happine&s;s than ob&s;truct it. &mdash; And you al&s;o know that if I die without children &mdash; you &s;hall have a principal part of my fortune; &mdash; but damn it &mdash; I wi&s;h you had not u&s;ed the ma&s;k of friend&s;hip to &s;teal this young Lady away from her relations &mdash; 'tis hard that their good nature
<PB N="24" REF="30">mu&s;t be turned again&s;t their peace; &mdash; and hard, becau&s;e her whole family treat you with regard, that you &s;hould offer them the greate&s;t in&s;ult ima|ginable.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Cecil, I am more to be pitied than con|demned in this tran&s;action. &mdash; when I fir&s;t endea|voured to make my&s;elf agreeable to Mi&s;s Rivers, I imagined her family would readily countenance my addre&s;&s;es, and when I &s;ucceeded in that en|deavour, I had not time to declare my&s;elf in form, before her father entred into this engagement with Sidney. &mdash; The moment I heard it mention|ed, I wrote to him, offering him a <HI>carte blanche,</HI> and this morning a repetition of my offer was treated with contempt. &mdash; I have therefore been forc'd into the mea&s;ure you di&s;approve &s;o much&mdash; but I hope my conduct, in the character of the &s;on-in-law, will amply atone for any error in my behaviour as a friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well well, we mu&s;t make the be&s;t of a bad market, &mdash; her father has no right to force her inclinations; &mdash; 'tis equally cruel and unju&s;t; there|fore you may depend upon my utmo&s;t endeavours not only to a&s;&s;i&s;t you in carrying her off, but in appea&s;ing all family re&s;entments. &mdash; For really, you are &s;o often in the wrong, that one mu&s;t &s;tand by you a little when you are in the right, &mdash; &s;o I &s;hall be ready for you kin&s;man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Cecil, this is hone&s;t &mdash; this is really friendly &mdash; and you &s;hall abu&s;e me a whole twelvemonth without my an&s;wering a &s;yllable &mdash;
<PB N="25" REF="31">but for the pre&s;ent I mu&s;t leave you &mdash; yonder I &s;ee Mi&s;s Rivers &mdash; we have &s;ome little matters to talk of &mdash; you under&s;tand me &mdash; and now &mdash;</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>For a torrent of rapture and non&s;en&s;e. &mdash; What egregious puppies does this unaccountable love make of young fellows: Nay, for that matter, what egregious puppies does it not make of old ones? &mdash; <HI>ecce &s;ignum.</HI> &mdash; 'Tis a comfort though, that no body knows I am a puppy in this re&s;pect but my&s;elf. &mdash; Here was I fancying that all the partiality I felt for poor Horten&s;ia Marchmont, proceeded from my friend&s;hip for her father &mdash; when upon an hone&s;t examination into my own heart &mdash; I find it principally ari&s;es from my regard for her&s;elf. &mdash; I was in hopes a change of objects would have driven the baggage out of my thoughts, &mdash; and I went to France; &mdash; but I am come home with a &s;ettled re&s;olution of a&s;king her to marry a &s;lovenly ra&s;cal of fifty, who is to be &s;ure a very likely &s;wain for a young lady to fall in love with; &mdash; but who knows &mdash; the mo&s;t &s;en&s;ible women have &s;ometimes &s;trange ta&s;tes; &mdash; and yet it mu&s;t be a very &s;trange ta&s;te, that can po&s;&s;ibly approve of my overtures. &mdash; I'll go cautiou&s;ly to work however, &mdash; and &s;olicit her as for a friend of my own age and fortune; &mdash; &s;o that if &s;he refu&s;es me, which is probable enough &mdash; I &s;han't expo&s;e my&s;elf to her contempt. &mdash; What a ridiculous figure is an old fool &s;ighing at the feet of a young woman. &mdash; Zounds, I wonder how the grey-headed dotards have the impudence to a&s;k a blooming girl of twenty to throw her&s;elf away upon a moving mummy, or a walking &s;keleton.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="26" REF="32">
<HI>The</HI> SCENE <HI>changes to an Apartment in</HI> Lady BETTY's <HI>Hou&s;e.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Lady BETTY <HI>and</HI> Mrs. HARLEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>You can't think, Emmy, how my &s;pirits are agitated; &mdash; I wonder what my Lord can want with me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, try and collect your&s;elf a little &mdash; he is ju&s;t coming up, &mdash; I mu&s;t retire. &mdash; Courage, my dear creature, this once &mdash; and the day's our own, I warrant you.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> WINWORTH, <HI>bowing very low.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here he is! &mdash; Ble&s;s me, what a flutter I am in!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your Lady&s;hip's mo&s;t obedient.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Won't your Lord&s;hip be &s;eated? &mdash; He &s;eems exce&s;&s;ively confus'd.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have taken the liberty, Madam &mdash; How &s;he awes me now I am alone with her!</P>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay, Madam, I have taken the liberty to &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="27" REF="33">
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg, my Lord, you won't con&s;ider an apolo|gy in the lea&s;t &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your Lady&s;hip is extremely obliging &mdash; and yet I am fearful &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope your Lord&s;hip will con&s;ider me as a friend, &mdash; and therefore lay a&s;ide this unnece&s;&s;ary ceremony.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do con&s;ider you, Madam, as a friend; &mdash; as an ine&s;timable friend &mdash; and I am this moment come to &s;olicit you upon a &s;ubject of the utmo&s;t importance to my happine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>Lord! what is he going to &s;ay?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay, my Lord, that you cannot &s;peak to me on any &s;ubject of importance without engaging my greate&s;t attention.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>You honour me too much, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not in the lea&s;t, my Lord &mdash; for there is not a per&s;on in the world who wi&s;hes your happine&s;s with greater cordiality.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="28" REF="34">
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>You eternally oblige me, Madam &mdash; and I can now take courage to tell you, that my happi|ne&s;s, in a mo&s;t material degree, depends upon your Lady&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>On me, my Lord? &mdash; Ble&s;s me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Madam, on your Lady&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>Mrs. Harley was right, and I &s;hall &s;ink with confu&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis on this bu&s;ine&s;s, Madam, I have taken the liberty of reque&s;ting the pre&s;ent interview, &mdash; and as I find your Lady&s;hip &s;o generou&s;ly ready &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, my Lord, I mu&s;t confe&s;s &mdash; I &s;ay, I mu&s;t acknowledge, my Lord, &mdash; that if your hap|pine&s;s depends upon me &mdash; I &s;hould not be very much pleas'd to &s;ee you mi&s;erable.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your Lady&s;hip is benignity it&s;elf; &mdash; but as I want words to expre&s;s my &s;en&s;e of this obligation &mdash; I &s;hall proceed at once to my reque&s;t, nor tre&s;pa&s;s upon your patience by an ineffectual com|pliment to your genero&s;ity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you plea&s;e, my Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, Madam, my reque&s;t is, that I may have your con&s;ent &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="29" REF="35">
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is &s;o &s;udden, my Lord! &mdash; &s;o unexpected!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Madam, it is &s;o; &mdash; yet, if I cou'd but engage your acquie&s;cence &mdash; I might &s;till think of a double union on the day which makes my cou&s;in happy &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord &mdash; I really don't know how to an|&s;wer: &mdash; Does'nt your Lord&s;hip think this is ra|ther precipitating matters?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>No man, Madam, can be too &s;peedy in pro|moting his happine&s;s: &mdash; If, therefore, I might pre&s;ume to hope for your concurrence &mdash; I woud'nr altogether &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>My concurrence, my Lord! &mdash; &s;ince it is &s;o e&s;&s;entially nece&s;&s;ary to your peace I cannot refu&s;e any longer. &mdash; Your great merit will ju&s;tify &s;o im|mediate a compliance &mdash; and I &s;hall &s;tand excu&s;ed of all. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, Madam, I don't de&s;pair of the Lady's &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know your Lady&s;hip can ea&s;ily prevail upon her to overlook an immaterial punctilio, and therefore &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Lady, my Lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="30" REF="36">
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Madam, Mi&s;s Marchmont; if &s;he finds my addre&s;&s;es &s;upported by your Lady&s;hip, will, in all probability, be ea&s;ily induced to receive them, &mdash; and then, your Lady&s;hip knows &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Marchmont! my Lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Madam, Mi&s;s Marchmont. &mdash; Since your final di&s;approbation of tho&s;e hopes which I was once pre&s;umptuous enough to entertain of calling your Lady&s;hip mine, the angui&s;h of a rejected pa&s;&s;ion has render'd me inconceivably wretched, and I &s;ee no way of mitigating the &s;everity of my &s;ituation but in the e&s;teem of this amiable woman, who knows how tenderly I have been attached to you, and who&s;e goodne&s;s will induce her, I am well convinced, to alleviate, as much as po&s;&s;ible, the greatne&s;s of my di&s;appointment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your Lord&s;hip is undoubtedly right in your opi|nion &mdash; and I am infinitely concern'd to have been the involuntary cau&s;e of unea&s;ine&s;s to you; &mdash; but Mi&s;s Marchmont, my Lord &mdash; &s;he will merit your utmo&s;t &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know &s;he will, Madam &mdash; and it rejoices me to &s;ee you &s;o highly pleas'd with my intention.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, I am quite delighted with it!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>I knew I &s;hould plea&s;e you by it. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="31" REF="37">
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>You can't imagine how you have pleas'd me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>How noble is this goodne&s;s! &mdash; Then, Madam, I may expect your Lady&s;hip will be my advocate? &mdash; The inju&s;tice which fortune has done Mi&s;s Marchmont's merit, obliges me to act with a double degree of circum&s;pection; &mdash; for, when virtue is unhappily plung'd into difficulties, 'tis entitled to an aditional &s;hare of veneration.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>How has my folly undone me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will not tre&s;pa&s;s any longer upon your Lady|&s;hip's lei&s;ure, than ju&s;t to ob&s;erve, that though I have &s;olicited your friend&s;hip on this occa&s;ion, I mu&s;t, neverthele&s;s, beg you will not be too much my friend. &mdash; I know Mi&s;s Marchmont would make any &s;acrifice to oblige you; &mdash; and if her gratitude &s;hould appear in the lea&s;t concerned, &mdash; This is a nice point, my dear Lady Betty, and I mu&s;t not wound the peace of any per&s;on's bo&s;om, to recover the tranquility of my own.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Mrs. HARLEY, <HI>who &s;peaks.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<P>Well, my dear, is it all over?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is all over indeed, Emmy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>But why that &s;orrowful tone &mdash; and melancholly countenance? Mu&s;t'nt I wi&s;h you joy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="32" REF="38">
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, I am the mo&s;t mi&s;erable woman in the world! &mdash; Would you believe it? &mdash; The bu&s;i|ne&s;s of this interview was to reque&s;t my intere&s;t in his favour with Mi&s;s Marchmont.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>With Mi&s;s Marchmont! &mdash; Then there is not one atom of &s;incere affection in the univer&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>As to that, I have rea&s;on to think his &s;enti|ments for me are as tender as ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>He gives you a pretty proof of his tenderne&s;s, truly, when he a&s;ks your a&s;&s;i&s;tance to marry ano|ther woman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Had you but &s;een his confu&s;ion, &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>He might well be confu&s;ed, when, after court|ing you the&s;e three years, he cou'd think of ano|ther, and that too at the very moment in which you were ready to oblige him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>There has been a &s;ort of fatality in the affair &mdash; and I am puni&s;h'd but too ju&s;tly: &mdash; The wo|man that wants candour where &s;he is addre&s;s'd by a man of merit, wants a very e&s;&s;ential virtue; and &s;he who can delight in the anxiety of a wor|thy mind, is little to be pitied when &s;he feels the &s;harpe&s;t &s;tings of anxiety in her own.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY,</SPEAKER>
<P>But what do you intend to do with regard to this extraordinary reque&s;t of Lord Winworth; &mdash; will you really &s;uffer him to marry Mi&s;s March mont?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="33" REF="39">
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why what can I do? If it was improper for me, before I knew any thing of his de&s;ign in re|gard to Mi&s;s Marchmont, to in&s;inuate the lea&s;t de&s;ire of hearing him again on the &s;ubject of his heart, 'tis doubly improper now, when I &s;ee he has turn'd his thoughts on another woman, and when this woman, be&s;ides, is one of my mo&s;t valuable friends.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, courage Lady Betty &mdash; we are'nt yet in a de&s;perate &s;ituation &mdash; Mi&s;s Marchmont loves you &mdash; as her&s;elf &mdash; and woud'nt, I dare &s;ay, accept the fir&s;t man in the world, if it gave you the lea&s;t unea&s;ine&s;s. &mdash; I'll go to her therefore this very moment &mdash; tell her at once how the ca&s;e is &mdash; and my life for it, her obligations to you &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stay, Emmy &mdash; I conjure you &s;tay &mdash; and as you value my peace of mind be for ever &s;ilent on this &s;ubject. &mdash; Mi&s;s Marchmont has no obliga|tions to me; &mdash; &s;ince our acquaintance I have been the only per&s;on obliged; &s;he has given me a power of &s;erving the worthie&s;t young creature in the world, and &s;o far has laid me under the greate&s;t obligation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why my dear &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;uppo&s;e I could be mean enough to think an apartment in my hou&s;e, a place in my chariot, a &s;eat at my table, and a little annuity in ca&s;e of my decea&s;e, were obligations, when I continu|ally enjoy &s;uch a happine&s;s as her friend&s;hip and her company. &mdash; Do you think they are obliga|tions which &s;hould make a woman of her fine
<PB N="34" REF="40">&s;en&s;e, reject the mo&s;t amiable man exi&s;ting, e&s;pe|cially in her circum&s;tances, where he has the ad|ditional recommendation of an elevated rank and an affluent fortune: &mdash; This wou'd be ex|acting intere&s;t with a witne&s;s for trifles, and, in&s;tead of having any little merit to claim from my behaviour to her, I &s;hou'd be the mo&s;t in|exorable of all u&s;urers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well but &s;uppo&s;e Mi&s;s Marchmont &s;hou'd not like my Lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not like him &mdash; why will you &s;uppo&s;e an im|po&s;&s;ibility?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>But let us &s;uppo&s;e it for argument &s;ake.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why I cannot &s;ay but it would plea&s;e me above all things: &mdash; For &s;till, Emmy, I am a wo|man, and feel this unexpected misfortune with the keene&s;t &s;en&s;ibility: &mdash; It kills me to think of his being another's, but if he mu&s;t, I wou'd ra|ther &s;ee him her's than any woman's in the uni|ver&s;e. &mdash; But I'll talk no more upon this &s;ubject, 'till I acquaint her with his propo&s;al; and yet, Emmy, how &s;evere a trial mu&s;t I go through.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, and you mo&s;t richly de&s;erve it.</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<TRAILER><HI>End of the &s;econd</HI> ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="act">
<PB N="35" REF="41">
<HEAD>ACT III.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE Lady BETTY's <HI>Garden.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>Sir HARRY, Mi&s;s RIVERS <HI>and</HI> SALLY <HI>cro&s;s at the head of the &s;tage;</HI> Colonel RIVERS <HI>ob&s;erving them.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>IN clo&s;e conver&s;ation with Sir Harry this half hour, at the remote&s;t part of the garden. &mdash; Why, what am I to think of all this. &mdash; Does'nt &s;he know I have refu&s;ed him: &mdash; Does'nt &s;he know her&s;elf engaged to Sidney? &mdash; There's &s;omething mean and pitiful in &s;u&s;picion: &mdash; But &s;till there is &s;omething that alarms me in this affair; and who knows how far the happine&s;s of my child may be at &s;take. &mdash; Women, after all, are &s;trange things; &mdash; they have more &s;en&s;e than we generally allow them &mdash; but they have al&s;o more vanity. &mdash; 'Tis'nt for want of under&s;tanding they err, &mdash; but through an in&s;atiable love of &s;lattery. &mdash; They know very well when they are committing a fault, but de&s;truction wears &s;o bewitching a form, that they rebel again&s;t the &s;en&s;e of their own conviction &mdash; and never trouble them&s;elves about con&s;equences till they are actully undone. &mdash; But here they come, &mdash; I don't like this li&s;tening: &mdash; Yet the meanne&s;s of the action mu&s;t for once be ju&s;tified by the nece&s;&s;ity.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Retires behind a clump of trees.]</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Mi&s;s RIVERS, Sir HARRY <HI>and</HI> SALLY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, Sir Harry, you upbraid me very unju&s;tly. &mdash; I feel the refu&s;al which my father has given you &s;everely. &mdash; Neverthele&s;s I mu&s;t not con&s;ent to you propo&s;al. &mdash; An elopement wou'd, I am &s;ure,
<PB N="36" REF="42">break his heart, &mdash; and as he is wholly ignorant of my partiality for you. &mdash; I cannot accu&s;e him of unkindne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS, <HI>behind.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So! &s;o! &s;o! &s;o!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then, my dear Mi&s;s Rivers, woud'nt you give me leave to mention the prepo&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion with which you honour me to the old Gentleman?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>The old gentleman &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e I was in hopes my father would have li&s;ten'd to your application, without putting me to the painful nece&s;&s;ity of acknowledging my &s;entiments in your favour; and becau&s;e I fear'd that unle&s;s the application was approved, on ac|count of it's intrin&s;ic genero&s;ity, there was no|thing which cou'd po&s;&s;ibly work upon the firmne&s;s of his temper.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well &s;aid daughter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SALLY.</SPEAKER>
<P>The firmne&s;s of your father's temper, madam! &mdash; The ob&s;tinacy you &s;hou'd &s;ay! &mdash; Sir Harry, as I live and breathe, there is'nt &s;o ob&s;tinate, &s;o perver&s;e, and &s;o peevi&s;h an old devil in all England.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank you, Mrs. Sally.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sally, I in&s;i&s;t that when you &s;peak of my father, you always &s;peak of him with re&s;pect. &mdash; 'Tis'nt your knowledge of &s;ecrets which &s;hall ju&s;ti|fy the&s;e freedoms; &mdash; for I wou'd rather every
<PB N="37" REF="43">thing was di&s;covered this minute than hear him mention'd with &s;o impudent a &s;imiliarity by his &s;ervants.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SALLY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well Madam, I beg pardon; &mdash; but you know the Colonel, where he once determines is never to be alter'd; &mdash; &s;o that call this &s;teadine&s;s of temper by what name you plea&s;e &mdash; 'tis likely to make you mi&s;erable, unle&s;s you embrace the pre&s;ent opportunity, and go off, like a woman of &s;pirit, with the object of your affections.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a damn'd jade it is!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, my dear Mi&s;s Rivers, Sally advi&s;es you like a true friend; &mdash; and I am &s;atisfied your own good &s;en&s;e mu&s;t &s;ecretly argue on her &s;ide the que&s;tion. &mdash; The only alternative you have is to fly and be happy &mdash; or &s;tay and be mi&s;erable: &mdash; You have your&s;elf acknowledg'd my ever adorable. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, damn your adorables!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay, Madam, you have your&s;elf acknow|ledg'd that there is no hope what&s;oever of work|ing upon the Colonel's tenderne&s;s by acquainting him with our mutual affection: &mdash; On the contra|ry 'tis likely that had he the lea&s;t &s;u&s;picion of my being honour'd with your regard, he wou'd drag you in&s;tantly to his favourite Sidney, who is &s;o utterly in&s;en&s;ible of your merit, &mdash; and who, if he has a pa&s;&s;ion for any body, is, I am confident, devoted to Mi&s;s Marchmont.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="38" REF="44">
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why what a lye has the ra&s;cal trump'd up here again&s;t poor Sidney?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Sir Harry, what wou'd you have me do?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>There! &mdash; Her dear Sir Harry!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>My ever adorable Mi&s;s Rivers &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, &s;he can't &s;tand the&s;e ever adorables.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>This exce&s;s of filial affection is extremely amiable: &mdash; but it ought by no means to render you forgetful of what is due to your&s;elf. &mdash; Con|&s;ider, Madam, if you have been treated with tenderne&s;s, you have repaid that tenderne&s;s with duty, and have &s;o far di&s;charged this mighty obligation!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>A pretty method of &s;ettling accounts truly!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't, my dear Sir Harry, &s;peak in this neg|ligent manner of my father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Kind creature!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>From what I have urg'd you mu&s;t &s;ee, Madam, that though you are &s;o ready to &s;acrifice your peace for your father, he &s;ets a greater value upon a trifing promi&s;e than upon your happine&s;s: &mdash;
<PB N="39" REF="45">Judge, therefore, whether his repo&s;e &s;hould be dearer to you, than your own; and judge too whether to prevent the breach of his word, you &s;hou'd vow eternal tenderne&s;s to a man you mu&s;t eternally dete&s;t, and violate even your veracity to kill the object of your love?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good heav'n, what &s;hall I do?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SALLY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do &mdash; Madam &mdash; go off to be &s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll wring that hu&s;&s;ey's head off.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>On my knees, Madam, let me beg you will con&s;ult your own happine&s;s, and, in your own, the happine&s;s of your father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, now he kneels, 'tis all over.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Colonel, Madam, has great &s;en&s;ibility, and the con&s;ciou&s;ne&s;s that he him&s;elf has been the cau&s;e of your unhappine&s;s will &s;ill him with endle&s;s regret: &mdash; Whereas, by e&s;caping with me, the ca&s;e will be utterly otherwi&s;e. &mdash; When he &s;ees we are in&s;eparably united, and hears with how unabating an a&s;&s;iduity I labour to merit the ble&s;&s;ing of your hand, a little time will nece&s;&s;arily make us friends; and I have great hopes that before the end of three months we &s;hall be the favourites of the whole family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>You'll be cur&s;edly mi&s;taken though. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="40" REF="46">
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;peak, my dear Mi&s;s Rivers &mdash; &s;peak and pronounce my fate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Harry you have convinced me. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, I knew he wou'd. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>And provided you here give me a &s;olemn a&s;&s;u|rance, that the moment we are married, you will employ every po&s;&s;ible method of effecting a recon|ciliation &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>You con&s;ent to go off with me the fir&s;t oppor|tunity &mdash; a thou&s;and thanks, my Angel for this ge|nerous conde&s;cen&s;ion, &mdash; and when &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>There is no occa&s;ion for profe&s;&s;ions, Sir Harry, &mdash; I rely implicitly on your tenderne&s;s and your honour. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SALLY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Madam, you have tran&s;ported your poor Sally by this noble re&s;olution.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I dare &s;ay &s;he has &mdash; but I may chance to cool your tran&s;port in a hor&s;e-pond. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am obliged to you, Sally, for the part you take in my affairs, and I purpo&s;e that you &s;hall be the companion of my flight.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SALLY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shall I, Madam! &mdash; you are too good &mdash; and I am &s;ure I &s;houd'nt like to live in my old ma&s;ter's hou&s;e, when you are out of the family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="41" REF="47">
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be unea&s;y on that account.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Suffer me now, my dear Mi&s;s Rivers, &s;ince you have been thus generou&s;ly kind, to inform you that a coach and &s;ix will be ready punctually at twelve, at the &s;ide of the little paddock at the back of Lady Betty's garden. &mdash; There's a clo&s;e walk, you know from the garden to the place, and I'll meet you at the &s;pot to conduct you to the coach.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I am &s;trangely apprehen&s;ive, &mdash; but I'll be there. &mdash; However, 'tis now high time for us to &s;eparate, &mdash; my father's eyes are generally every where &mdash; and I am impatient &s;ince it is determin|ed &mdash; till our de&s;ign is executed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, I don't in the lea&s;t doubt it. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Till twelve then farewell my charmer. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERs.</SPEAKER>
<P>You do what you will with me. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt &s;eparately.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS <HI>comes forward.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You do what you will with me! Why what a fool, what an idiot was I &mdash; ever to &s;uppo&s;e I had a daughter. &mdash; From the moment of her birth &mdash; to this cur&s;ed hour, I have labour'd, I have toil'd for happine&s;s, and now, when I fancy'd my&s;elf &s;ure of her tend're&s;t affection, &s;he ca&s;ts me off for ever. &mdash; By and by, &mdash; I &s;hall have this fellow at my feet, entreating my forgivene&s;s, and the world will think me an unfeeling mon&s;ter, if I don't give him my e&s;tate as a reward for having bla&s;ted my deare&s;t expectations. &mdash; The world
<PB N="42" REF="48">will think it &s;trange that I &s;hou'd not promote his felicity, becau&s;e he has utterly de&s;troyed mine; and my dutiful daughter will be &s;urprized if the tender ties of nature are not &s;trictly regarded in my conduct, though &s;he has violated the mo&s;t &s;acred of them all in her own. &mdash; Death and hell! who wou'd be a father? &mdash; There is yet one way left, &mdash; and, if that fails, &mdash; why, I never had a daughter. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>The</HI> SCENE <HI>changes to an Apartment. Enter</HI> Mi&s;s MARCHMONT <HI>and</HI> CECIL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, now Sir I mu&s;t tax you with unkind|ne&s;s, &mdash; know &s;omething that may po&s;&s;ibly be of con&s;equence to my welfare, &mdash; and yet decline to tell me! &mdash; Is this con&s;i&s;tent with the u&s;ual friend|&s;hip which I have met with from Mr. Cecil?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look'ye, Horten&s;ia, 'tis becau&s;e I &s;et a very great value on your e&s;teem that I find this unwill|ingne&s;s to explain my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, Sir, you grow every moment more and more my&s;terious. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well then, Horten&s;ia, if I thought you woud'nt be offended &mdash; I &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;ure, Sir, you will never &s;ay any thing to give me a rea&s;onable cau&s;e of offence. &mdash; I know your kindne&s;s for me too well, Sir. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where is the need of Sirring me at every word? &mdash; I de&s;ire you will lay a&s;ide this ceremony, and
<PB N="43" REF="49">treat me with the &s;ame freedom you do every body el&s;e, &mdash; the&s;e Sirs are &s;o cold, and &s;o di&s;tant. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed Sir, I can't &s;o ea&s;ily lay a&s;ide my re&s;pect as you imagine, for I have long con&s;idered you as a father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>As a father! &mdash; but that's a light in which I don't want to be con&s;ider'd. &mdash; As a father in|deed, &mdash; O &s;he's likely to think me a proper hu&s;|band for her, I can &s;ee that already.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why not Sir? &mdash; your years, &mdash; your friend&s;hip for my father, and your partiality for me, &s;uffi|ciently ju&s;tify the propriety of my epithet. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>My years! &mdash; Yes, I thought my years would be an invincible ob&s;tacle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>But pray Sir, &mdash; to the bu&s;ine&s;s upon which you wanted to &s;peak with me: &mdash; You don't con|&s;ider I am all this time upon the rack of my &s;ex's curio&s;ity. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then, Horten&s;ia, &mdash; I will proceed to the bu&s;ine&s;s &mdash; and a&s;k you, in one word, &mdash; if you have any di&s;inclination to be married?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is proceeding to bu&s;ine&s;s indeed Sir, &mdash; but ha &mdash; ha &mdash; ha! pray who have you de&s;igned me as a hu&s;band?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why what do you think of a man about my age?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="44" REF="50">
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Of your age Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, of my age. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Sir, what wou'd you advi&s;e me to think of him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>That is'nt the que&s;tion, for all your arch &s;ig|nificance of manner, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>O I am &s;ure you wou'd never recommend him to me as a hu&s;band Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>&mdash; So! &mdash; and why not pray?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e I am &s;ure you have too great a regard for me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>She gives me rare encouragement. <STAGE>[a&s;ide]</STAGE> &mdash; But do you imagine it impo&s;&s;ible for &s;uch a hu&s;band to love you very tenderly?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>No &mdash; Sir, &mdash; But do you imagine it po&s;&s;ible for me to love him very tenderly. &mdash; You &s;ee I have caught your own frankne&s;s Sir, &mdash; and an|&s;wer with as much ea&s;e as you que&s;tion me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>How lucky it was that I did not open my&s;elf directly to her. &mdash; O! I &s;hould have been mo&s;t purely contemptible.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="45" REF="51">
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>But pray, Sir, &mdash; have you, in reality, any meaning by the&s;e que&s;tions? &mdash; Is there actually any body who has &s;poken to you on my account?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Horten&s;ia, there is a fellow, a very fooli&s;h fel|low, for whom I have &s;ome value, that entertains the &s;incere&s;t affection for you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, indeed, Sir, I am very unhappy, &mdash; for I cannot encourage the addre&s;&s;es of any body.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>No?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, Sir! I had but two friends in the world, &mdash; your&s;elf and Lady Betty, &mdash; and I am, with ju&s;tice apprehen&s;ive that neither will con&s;ider me long with any degree of regard, &mdash; Lady Betty has a propo&s;al from Lord Winworth of the &s;ame nature with yours, in which I fear &s;he will &s;trongly in|tere&s;t her&s;elf, &mdash; and I mu&s;t be under the painful nece&s;&s;ity of di&s;obliging you both, from an utter impo&s;&s;ibility of li&s;tening to either of your recom|mendations.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you, Horten&s;ia, not to alarm your&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Sir, I have always con&s;idered you with reverence, and it would make me inconceivably wretched if you imagin'd I was actuated upon this occa&s;ion by any ridiculous &s;ingularity of &s;enti|ment. &mdash; I wou'd do much to plea&s;e you, &mdash; and I &s;carcely know what I &s;hould refu&s;e to Lady Betty's
<PB N="46" REF="52">reque&s;t; &mdash; but, Sir, though it di&s;tre&s;&s;es me ex|ceedingly to di&s;cover it, &mdash; I mu&s;t tell you I have not a heart to di&s;po&s;e of.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>How's this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>At the &s;ame time, I mu&s;t however, tell you, that my affections are &s;o plac'd as to make it wholly impo&s;&s;ible for me ever to change my &s;ituation. &mdash; This acknowledgment of a prepo&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion, Sir, may be incon&s;i&s;tent with the nice re&s;erve which is proper for my &s;ex, &mdash; but it is nece&s;&s;ary to ju&s;tify me in a ca&s;e where my gratitude might be rea&s;onably &s;u&s;|pected, and when I recollect to whom it is made, I hope it will be doubly entitled to an excu&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your candour, Horten&s;ia, needs no apology, &mdash; but as you have tru&s;ted me thus far with your &s;ecret, &mdash; may'nt I know why you can have no pro&s;pect of being united to the object of your affections?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e, Sir, he is engaged to a mo&s;t de&s;erv|ing young lady, and will be married to her in a few days: &mdash; In &s;hort, Mr. Sidney is the Man for whom I entertain this &s;ecret partiality: &mdash; You &s;ee, therefore, that my partiality is hopele&s;s, &mdash; but you &s;ee, at the &s;ame time, how utterly im|proper it would be for me to give a lifele&s;s hand to another while he is entirely ma&s;ter of my af|fections. &mdash; It would be a meanne&s;s of which I think my&s;elf incapable, and I &s;hould be quite un|worthy the honour of any de&s;erving hand, if, cir|cum&s;tanc'd in this manner, I could ba&s;ely &s;toop to accept it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="47" REF="53">
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>You intere&s;t me &s;trangely in your &s;tory, Hor|ten&s;ia: &mdash; But has Sidney any idea? &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>None in the lea&s;t. &mdash; Before the match with Mi&s;s Rivers was in agitation he made addre&s;&s;es to me, though privately; and, I mu&s;t own, his ten|derne&s;s, join'd to his good qualities, &s;oon gave me impre&s;&s;ions in his favour. &mdash; But, Sir, I was a poor orphan, wholly dependant upon the genero&s;ity of others, and he was a younger brother of a fa|mily, great in his birth, but contracted in his circum&s;tances. &mdash; What cou'd I do? &mdash; It was not in my power to make his fortune, &mdash; and I had too much pride, or too much affection, to think of de&s;troying it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are a good girl, &mdash; a very good girl; &mdash; but &s;urely if Lady Betty knows any thing of this matter there can be no danger of her recommend|ing Lord Winworth &s;o earne&s;tly to your atten|tion. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>There, Sir, is my principle misfortune. &mdash; Lady Betty is, of all per&s;ons, the lea&s;t proper to be made acquainted with it. &mdash; Her heart is in the marriage between Mi&s;s Rivers and Mr. Sidney; and, had &s;he the lea&s;t idea of my &s;enti|timents for him, or of his inclination for me, I am po&s;itive it would immediately fru&s;trate the match. &mdash; On this account, Sir, I have carefully con|cealed the &s;ecret of my wi&s;hes, &mdash; and, on this account, I mu&s;t &s;till continue to conceal it. &mdash; My heart &s;hall break before it &s;hall be worthle&s;s;
<PB N="48" REF="54">&mdash; and I &s;hould dete&s;t my&s;elf for ever if I was ca|pable of e&s;tabli&s;hing my own peace at the expence of my benefactre&s;s's fir&s;t wi&s;h, and the de&s;ire of her whole family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds, what can be the matter with my eyes! &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>My life was mark'd out early by calamity, &mdash; and the fir&s;t light I beheld was purchas'd with the lo&s;s of a mother. &mdash; The grave &s;natched away the be&s;t of fathers ju&s;t as I came to know the value of &s;uch a ble&s;&s;ing; &mdash; and had'nt it been for the exalted goodne&s;s of others, I, who once expe|rienc'd the un&s;peakable plea&s;ure of relieving the nece&s;&s;itous, had my&s;elf, perhaps, felt the imme|diate want of bread; &mdash; and &s;hall I ungratefully &s;ting the bo&s;om which has thus benevolently cheri&s;hed me? &mdash; Shall I ba&s;ely wound the peace of tho&s;e who have re&s;cu'd me from de&s;pair, &mdash; and &s;tab at their tranquility in the very moment they honour me with protection? &mdash; O, Mr. Cecil! they de&s;erve every &s;acrifice which I can make. &mdash; May the benignant hand of Providence &s;hower endle&s;s happine&s;s upon their heads, and may the &s;weets of a &s;till-encrea&s;ing felicity be their portion, whatever becomes of me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Horten&s;ia, &mdash; I can't &s;tay with you. &mdash; My eyes are exceedingly painful of late; &mdash; what the devil can be the matter with them? &mdash; But, let me tell you before I go, that you &s;hall be happy after all; &mdash; that you &s;hall, I promi&s;e you; &mdash; but I &s;ee Lady Betty coming this way &mdash; and I cannot en|ter into explanations, &mdash; yet, do you hear, &mdash;
<PB N="49" REF="55">don't &s;uppo&s;e I am angry with you for refu&s;ing my friend, &mdash; don't &s;uppo&s;e &s;uch a thing, I charge you; &mdash; for he has too much pride to force him|&s;elf upon any woman, and too much humanity to make any woman mi&s;erable. &mdash; He is be&s;ides a very fooli&s;h fellow, and it does'nt &s;ignify &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LADY BETTY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, my dear Horten&s;ia, I am come again to a&s;k you what you think of Lord Winworth. &mdash; We were interrupted before, &mdash; and I want, as &s;oon as po&s;&s;ible, for the rea&s;on I hinted, to know your real opinion of him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have long known my real opinion of him, Lady Betty. &mdash; You know I always thought him a very amiable man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[with impatience.]</STAGE>
<P>Do you think him an amiable man?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>The whole world thinks as I do in this re&s;pect,&mdash; yet, &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, &s;he loves him, 'tis plain; and there is no hope after this declaration &mdash; <STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE> &mdash; His Lord|&s;hip merits your good opinion, I a&s;&s;ure you Mi&s;s Marchmont.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>Yes, I &s;ee by this ceremony that &s;he is offended at my coolne&s;s to the propo&s;al.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have hinted to you, Mi&s;s Marchmont, that my Lord reque&s;ted I would exert my little intere&s;t with you in his favour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="50" REF="56">
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>The little intere&s;t your Lady&s;hip has with me, &mdash; the little intere&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be di&s;plea&s;ed with me, my dear Horten|&s;ia, &mdash; I know my intere&s;t with you is con&s;iderable. &mdash;I know you love me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I would &s;acrifice my life for you, Lady Betty: For what had that life been without your gene|ro&s;ity &mdash; ?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you love me, Horten&s;ia, never mention any thing of this nature.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are too good. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>But to my Lord Winworth. &mdash; He has earne&s;tly reque&s;ted I would become his advocate with you. &mdash; He has entirely got the better of his former attachments, and there can be no doubt of his making you an excellent hu&s;band.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>His Lord&s;hip does me infinite honour, &mdash; never|thele&s;s &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[eagerly.]</STAGE>
<P>Neverthele&s;s, what my dear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay, notwith&s;tanding, I think my&s;elf highly honour'd by his &s;entiments in my favour; &mdash; 'tis utterly impo&s;&s;ible for me to return his affection.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="51" REF="57">
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[&s;urprized.]</STAGE>
<P>Impo&s;&s;ible for you to return his affection!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>I knew what an intere&s;t &s;he wou'd take in this affair.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>And do you really &s;ay you can't give him a fa|vourable an&s;wer? &mdash; How fortunate!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do, my dear Lady Betty,&mdash;I can honour, I can reverence him, &mdash; but I cannot feel that tenderne&s;s for his per&s;on which I imagine to be nece&s;&s;ary both for his happine&s;s and my own.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my word, my dear, you are extremely difficult in your choice, and if Lord Winworth is not capable of in&s;piring you with tenderne&s;s &mdash; I don't know who is likely to &s;ucceed; for, in my opinion, there is not a man in England po&s;&s;e&s;|&s;ed of more per&s;onal accompli&s;hments.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>And yet, great as the&s;e accompli&s;hments are, my dear Lady Betty, they never excited your ten|ne&s;s. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, all this is very true, my dear, &mdash; but, though I felt no tenderne&s;s, &mdash; yet I &mdash; to be &s;ure, I &mdash; that is &mdash; I &s;ay, neverthele&s;s. &mdash; This is be|yond my hopes.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>She's di&s;tre&s;s'd that I decline the propo&s;al. &mdash; Her friend&s;hip for us both is generou&s;ly warm. &mdash; and &s;he imagines I am equally in&s;en&s;ible to his merit, and my own intere&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="52" REF="58">
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, my dear, I &s;ee your emotion &mdash; and I heartily beg your pardon for &s;aying &s;o much. &mdash; I &s;hould be inexpre&s;&s;ibly concern'd if I thought you made any &s;acrifice on this occa&s;ion to me. &mdash; My Lord, to be &s;ure, po&s;&s;e&s;&s;es a very high place in my e&s;teem, &mdash; but &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Lady Betty, what can I do? &mdash; I &s;ee you are offended with me, &mdash; and yet &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I offended with you, my dear! &mdash; far from it; I commend your re&s;olution extremely, &s;ince my Lord is not a man to your ta&s;te. &mdash; Offended with you! why &s;hould I take the liberty to be offended with you? &mdash; A pre&s;umption of that nature &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, Lady Betty, this affair makes me very unhappy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, my dear, you talk very &s;trangely; &mdash; &s;o far from being &s;orry that you have refus'd my Lord &mdash; I am pleas'd, &mdash; infinitely pleas'd, &mdash; that is, &s;ince he was not agreeable to you. &mdash; Be &s;atisfied your acceptance of him would have given me no plea&s;ure in the world, &mdash; I a&s;&s;ure you it wou'd'nt, &mdash; on the contrary, as matters are &s;ituated, I wou'd'nt for the world have you give him the &s;malle&s;t encouragement.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[alone.]</STAGE>
<P>I &s;ee &s;he's greatly di&s;appointed at my refu&s;al of an offer &s;o highly to my advantage, &mdash; I &s;ee, moreover, &s;he's griev'd that his Lord&s;hip &s;hould
<PB N="53" REF="59">meet with a &s;econd repul&s;e, and from a quarter too, where the genero&s;ity of his propo&s;al might be rea&s;onably expected to promi&s;e it &s;ucce&s;s. &mdash; How &s;urpriz'd &s;he &s;eem'd when I told her he cou'd'nt make an impre&s;&s;ion on my heart, and how eagerly &s;he endeavour'd to convince me that &s;he was pleas'd with my conduct; not con&s;idering that this very eagerne&s;s was a manife&s;t proof of her di&s;&s;atisfaction. &mdash; She is more intere&s;ted in this affair than I even thought &s;he would be, &mdash; and I &s;hould be completely mi&s;erable if &s;he cou'd &s;u&s;pect me of ingratitude. &mdash; As &s;he was &s;o zealous for the match I was certainly to blame in declining it &mdash; 'Tis not yet, however, too late. &mdash; She has been a thou&s;and parents to me, &mdash; and I will not regard my own wi&s;hes, when they are any way oppo&s;ite to her inclinations. &mdash; Poor Mr. Cecil! &mdash; Make me happy after all! &mdash; How? &mdash; Impo&s;&s;ible! &mdash; for I was born to nothing but misfortune. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
<TRAILER>End of the third <HI>ACT.</HI></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="act">
<PB N="54" REF="60">
<HEAD>ACT IV.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE <HI>an Apartment at</HI> Lady BETTY's <HI>Hou&s;e.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Lady BETTY <HI>and</HI> Mrs. HARLEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>THUS far, my dear Emmy, there is a gleam of hope. &mdash; She determined, po&s;i|tively determined, again&s;t my Lord: &mdash; And even &s;u&s;pected &s;o little of my partiality for him, that &s;he appeared under the greate&s;t anxiety le&s;t I &s;hould be offended with her refu&s;ing him: &mdash; And yet, &s;hall I own my folly to you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray do, my dear; &mdash; you'll &s;carcely believe it, &mdash; but I have follies of my own &s;ometimes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why you quite &s;urprize me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis very true for all that. &mdash; But to your bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then, greatly as I dreaded her appro|bation of the propo&s;al, &mdash; I was &s;ecretly hurt at her in&s;en&s;ibility to the per&s;onal attractions of his Lord&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't doubt, it my dear. &mdash; We think all the world &s;hould love what we are in love with our&s;elves.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="55" REF="61">
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your are right. &mdash; And though I was happy to find her re&s;olution &s;o agreeable to my wi&s;hes, my pride was not a little piqu'd to find it po&s;&s;ible for her to refu&s;e a man upon whom I had &s;o ardently plac'd my own affection. &mdash; The &s;urprize which I felt on this account threw a warmth into my expre&s;&s;ions, and made the generous girl appre|hen&s;ive that I was offended with her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, this is a &s;trange world we live in. &mdash; That a woman without a &s;hilling &s;hou'd refu&s;e an Earl with a fine per&s;on, and a great e&s;tate is the mo&s;t &s;urprizing affair I ever heard of. &mdash; Perhaps, Lady Betty, my Lord may take it in his head to go round the family: &mdash; If he &s;hould, my turn is next, and I a&s;&s;ure you, he &s;hall meet with a very different reception.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then you wou'd'nt be cruel, Emmy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why no! &mdash; Not very cruel. &mdash; I might give my&s;elf a few airs at fir&s;t. &mdash; I might blu&s;h a little, and look down. &mdash; Wonder what he cou'd find in me to attract his attention: &mdash; Then pulling up my head, with a to&s;s of di&s;dain, &mdash; de&s;ire him, if ever he &s;poke to me on that &s;ubject again, &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>To have a licence in his pocket, &mdash; that's all. &mdash; I would make &s;ure work of it at once, and leave it to your elevated minds to deal in delicate ab&s;ur|dities. &mdash; But I have a little anecdote for you,
<PB N="56" REF="62">which proves beyond a doubt that you are as much as ever in po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of Lord Winworth's affection.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is it, my dear Emmy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why about an hour ago, my woman, it &s;eems, and Arnold, my Lord's man, had a little con|ver&s;ation on this unexpected propo&s;al to Mi&s;s Marchmont; in which Arnold &s;aid, &mdash; <Q>Never tell me of your Mi&s;s Marchmonts, Mrs. Nel&s;on; &mdash; between our&s;elves &mdash; but let it go no farther &mdash; Lady Betty is &s;till the woman, and a &s;weet crea|ture &s;he is, that's the truth on't, but a little fanta&s;tical, and doesn't know her own mind &mdash;</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll a&s;&s;ure you! &mdash; Why Mr. Arnold is a wit.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, but hear him out: &mdash; <Q>Mrs. Nel&s;on, I know as much of my Lord's mind as any body; let him mary whom he plea&s;es, he'll never be rightly happy but with her Lady&s;hip; and I'd give a hundred guineas, with all my &s;oul, that it cou'd be a match.</Q> &mdash; The&s;e Nel|&s;on tells me were his very words. &mdash; Arnold is an intelligent fellow, and much in the confidence of his ma&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed I always thought my Lord happy in &s;o excellent a &s;ervant. &mdash; This intelligence is worth a world, my dear Emmy &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have been looking for your Lady&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="57" REF="63">
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you any thing particular, my dear Hor|ten&s;ia? &mdash; But why that gloom upon your fea|tures? &mdash; What gives you unea&s;ine&s;s, my &s;weet girl? Speak, and make me happy by &s;aying it is in my power to oblige you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis in your power, my dear Lady Betty, to oblige me highly &mdash; by forgiving the ungrateful di&s;regard which I ju&s;t now &s;hew'd to your recom|mendation of Lord Winworth.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>Now will I be hang'd if &s;he does not undo every thing by a fre&s;h &s;troke of delicacy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>And by informing his Lord&s;hip that I am ready to pay a proper obedience to your commands.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>O the devil take this elevation of &s;entiment!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>A proper obedience to my commands my dear! I really don't under&s;tand you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee how generou&s;ly you are concerned, for fear I &s;hou'd, upon this occa&s;ion, offer violence to my inclination: &mdash; But, Lady Betty, I &s;hou'd be infinitely more di&s;tre&s;s'd by the &s;malle&s;t act of ingratitude to you, than by any other misfor|tune. &mdash; I am therefore ready, in obedience to your wi&s;hes, to accept of his Lord&s;hip, and if I can't make him a fond wife, I will, at lea&s;t, make him a dutiful one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="58" REF="64">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>Now her delicacy is willing to be mi&s;erable.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>How cou'd you ever imagine, my dear Horten|&s;ia, that your rejection of Lord Winworth cou'd po&s;&s;ibly give me the &s;malle&s;t offence? &mdash; I have a great regard for his Lord&s;hip 'tis true, but I have a great regard for you al&s;o; and wou'd by no means wi&s;h to &s;ee his happine&s;s promoted at your ex|pence; &mdash; think of him therefore no more, and be a&s;&s;ur'd you oblige me in an infinitely higher degree by refu&s;ing than accepting him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>The more I &s;ee your Lady&s;hip's tenderne&s;s and delicacy, the more I &s;ee it nece&s;&s;ary to give an affirmative to Lord Winworth's propo&s;al. &mdash; Your genero&s;ity mu&s;t not get the better of my gratitude.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did ever two fools plague one another &s;o hear|tily with their delicacy and &s;entiment? &mdash;
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE> Dear Lady Betty, why don't you deal candidly with her? &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Her happine&s;s makes it nece&s;&s;ary now, and I will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, there's &s;ome &s;en&s;e in this. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your uncommon genero&s;ity, my dear Horten|&s;ia, has led you into an error &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not in the lea&s;t, Lady Betty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Still, Horten&s;ia, you are running into very great mi&s;takes. &mdash; My e&s;teem for Lord Winworth, let me now tell you &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="59" REF="65">
<HI>Enter</HI> WINWORTH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ladies, your mo&s;t obedient! &mdash; As I enter'd, Lady Betty, I heard you pronounce my name: &mdash; May I pre&s;ume to a&s;k, if you were talking to Mi&s;s Marchmont on the bu&s;ine&s;s I took the liber|ty of communicating to you this morning?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>Ay, now it's all over I &s;ee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, to be candid, my Lord, I have men|tioned your propo&s;al &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, my dear Mi&s;s Marchmont, and may I flatter my&s;elf that Lady Betty's interpo&s;ition will induce you to be propitious to my hopes? &mdash; The heart now offer'd to you, Madam, is a grateful one, and will retain an eternal &s;en&s;e of your good|ne&s;s. &mdash; Speak, therefore, my dear Mi&s;s March|mont, and kindly &s;ay you conde&s;cend to accept it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY,</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>So&mdash;here will be a comfortable piece of work.&mdash; I'll e'en retire and leave them to the con&s;equences of their ridiculous delicacy.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know not what to &s;ay, my Lord, &mdash; you have honoured me, greatly honoured me &mdash; but Lady Betty will acquaint you with my determination.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I acquaint him my dear&mdash;&s;urely you are your&s;elf the mo&s;t proper to&mdash;I &s;hall run di&s;tracted&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="60" REF="66">
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed madam I can't &s;peak to his lord&s;hip on this &s;ubject.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I a&s;&s;ure you, Horten&s;ia, 'tis a &s;ubject upon which I do not chu&s;e to enter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you had a kind an&s;wer from Mi&s;s March|mont, Lady Betty, I am &s;ure you would enter upon it readily: &mdash; But I &s;ee her reply very clear|ly in your reluctance to acquaint me with it.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why Madam will you force me to &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>And why Horten&s;ia? &mdash; What am I going to &s;ay? &mdash;</P>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't, my dear Ladies, &s;uffer me to di&s;tre&s;s you any longer, &mdash; to your friend&s;hip, Madam, I am as much indebted
<STAGE>[addre&s;&s;ing him&s;elf to Lady Betty.]</STAGE> as if I had been &s;ucce&s;sful, &mdash; and I &s;incerely wi&s;h Mi&s;s Marchmont that happine&s;s with a more de&s;erving man, which I find it impo&s;&s;ible for her to confer on me.</P>
<STAGE>[going.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>Now I have &s;ome hope.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord I entreat your &s;tay. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't call his Lord&s;hip back my dear, it will have an odd appearance.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="61" REF="67">
<HI>Enter</HI> Lord WINWORTH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>He is come back. &mdash; And I mu&s;t tell him what your unwillingne&s;s to influence my inclinations, makes you decline.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your commands Madam.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
<P>Now I am undone again!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am in &s;uch a &s;ituation my Lord that I can &s;carcely proceed &mdash; Lady Betty is cruelly kind to me &mdash; but as I know her wi&s;hes &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>My wi&s;hes, Mi&s;s Marchmont! &mdash; indeed my dear there is &s;uch a mi&s;take.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>There is no mi&s;taking your Lady&s;hip's good|ne&s;s, you are fearful to direct my re&s;olution, and I &s;hould be unkind to di&s;tre&s;s your friend&s;hip any longer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>You do di&s;tre&s;s me indeed Mi&s;s Marchmont.</P>
<STAGE>[half a&s;ide and &s;ighing.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am all expectation, Madam! &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am compell'd by gratitude to both, and from affection to my dear Lady Betty, to break through the common forms impos'd on our &s;ex, and to declare that I have no will but her Lady&s;hip's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is &s;o provoking.</P>
<STAGE>[a&s;ide.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="62" REF="68">
<SPEAKER>Lord WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ten thou&s;and thanks for this conde&s;cending goodne&s;s, Madam &mdash; a goodne&s;s which is additi|onally dear to me, as the re&s;ult of your determi|nation is pronounc'd by your own lips.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Lady Betty, I hope I have an&s;wer'd your wi&s;hes now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>You cannot conceive how &s;en&s;ibly I am touch'd with your behaviour my dear.</P>
<STAGE>[&s;ighs.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>You feel too much for me Lady Betty. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why I do feel &s;omething my dear &mdash; this un|expected event has fill'd my heart &mdash; and I am a little agitated. &mdash; But come, my dear, let us now go to the company.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>How generou&s;ly, Madam, do you intere&s;t your|&s;elf for my welfare!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>And for the welfare of all her friends:</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your Lord&s;hip is too good.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>But the bu&s;ine&s;s of her life is to promote the happine&s;s of others, and &s;he is con&s;tantly rewarded in the exerci&s;e of her own benignity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>You can't imagine how I am rewarded upon the pre&s;ent occa&s;ion I a&s;&s;ure your Lord&s;hip.</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt]</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="63" REF="69">
SCENE <HI>the Paddock behind</HI> Lady BETTY's <HI>Garden.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Mi&s;s RIVERS <HI>and</HI> SALLY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SALLY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Madam don't terrify your&s;elf with &s;uch gloomy reflections.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, Sally, you can't conceive my di&s;tre&s;s in this critical &s;ituation. &mdash; An elopement even from a tyrannical father, has &s;omething in it which mu&s;t &s;hock a delicate mind. &mdash; But when a woman flies from the protection of a parent, who merits the utmo&s;t return of her affection, &s;he mu&s;t be in&s;en|&s;ible indeed, if &s;he does not feel the &s;incere&s;t re|gret: &mdash; If he &s;houd'nt forgive me! &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SALLY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Madam he mu&s;t forgive you &mdash; are'nt you his child. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>And therefore I &s;houd'nt di&s;oblige him. &mdash; I am half di&s;tracted, &mdash; and I almo&s;t repent the promi&s;e I gave Sir Harry &mdash; when I con&s;ider how much my character may be le&s;&s;ened by this &s;tep, and recollect how it is likely to affect my unfor|tunate father. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SALLY.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I wonder where Sir Harry can be all this time. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h he was come. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SALLY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Courage, Madam &mdash; I hear him coming.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>It mu&s;t be he, let's run and meet him. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="64" REF="70">
Enter <HI>RIVERS.</HI> Sally &s;hrieks and runs off.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>My father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Theodora &mdash; your poor, abandoned, mi&s;er|able father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! Sir! &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Little, Theodora, did I imagine I &s;hou'd ever have cau&s;e to lament the hour of your birth, and le&s;s did I imagine when you arrived at an age to be perfectly acquainted with your duty, you wou'd throwevery &s;entiment of duty off. &mdash; In what, my dear, has your unhappy father been culpable, that you cannot bear his &s;ociety any longer? &mdash; What has he done to forfeit either your e&s;teem, or your affection? &mdash; From the moment of your birth to this unfortunate hour, he has laboured to promote your happine&s;s. &mdash; But how has his &s;olicitude on that account been rewarded? You now fly from the&s;e arms which have cheri&s;hed you with &s;o much tenderne&s;s, when gratitude, genero&s;ity and na|ture, &s;hould have twin'd me round your heart. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look back, infatuated child, upon my whole conduct &s;ince your approach to maturity: Hav'n't I contracted my own enjoyments on purpo&s;e to enlarge yours, and watched your very looks to anticipate your inclinations? Have I ever, with the ob&s;tinacy of other fathers, been partial in favour of any man to whom you made the &s;lighte&s;t objection. &mdash; Or have I ever &s;hewn
<PB N="65" REF="71">the lea&s;t de&s;ign of forcing your wi&s;hes to my own humour or caprice? On the contrary has'nt the engagement I have enter'd into been carried on<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> &s;eemingly with your own approbation. &mdash; And hav'n't you always appeared reconciled at lea&s;t to a marriage with Mr. Sidney?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;o a&s;ham'd of my&s;elf!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>How then, Theodora, have I merited a treat|ment of this nature? You have under&s;tanding, my dear, though you want filial affection, and my arguments mu&s;t have weight with your rea&s;on, however my tranquility may be the object of your contempt.&mdash;I lov'd you, Theodora, with the warm|e&s;t degree of paternal tenderne&s;s, and flatter'd my&s;elf the proofs I every day gave of that tender|ne&s;s, had made my peace of mind a matter of &s;ome importance to my child. &mdash; But, alas! a pal|try compliment from a coxcomb undoes the whole labour of my life; and the daughter whom I looked upon as the &s;upport of my declining years, betrays me in the un&s;u&s;pecting hour of &s;ecurity, and rewards with her per&s;on, the a&s;&s;a&s;&s;in who &s;tabs me to the heart. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hear me dear Sir, hear me &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do not come here, Theodora, to &s;top your flight, or put the &s;malle&s;t impediment in the way of your wi&s;hes. &mdash; Your per&s;on is your own, and I &s;corn to detain even my daughter by force, where &s;he is not bound to me by inclination. &mdash; Since therefore neither duty nor di&s;cretion, a regard for my peace, nor a &s;olicitude for your own wel|fare,
<PB N="66" REF="72">are able to detain you, &mdash; go to this man, who has taught you to obliterate the &s;entiments of nature, and gain'd a ready way to your heart, by expre&s;&s;ing a contempt for your father. &mdash; Go to him boldly, my child, and laugh at the pangs which tear this unhappy bo&s;om. &mdash; Be uniform|ly culpable, nor add the ba&s;ene&s;s of a de&s;pica|ble &s;light to the unpardonable want of a filial affection.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Going]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am the mo&s;t mi&s;erable creature in the world.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[Returns.]</STAGE>
<P>One thing more, Theodora, &mdash; and then fare|well for ever. &mdash; Though you come here to throw off the affection of a child, I will not quit this place, before I di&s;charge the duty of a parent, even to a romantic extravagance, and provide for your welfare, while you plunge me into the mo&s;t poignant of all di&s;tre&s;s. &mdash; In the doating hours of paternal blandi&s;hment, I have often promi&s;ed you a fortune of twenty thou&s;and pounds, when|ever you chang'd your &s;ituation. &mdash; This promi&s;e was indeed made when I thought you incapable either of ingratitude, or di&s;&s;imulation, &mdash; and when I fancied your per&s;on wou'd be given, where there was &s;ome rea&s;onable pro&s;pect of your hap|pine&s;s. &mdash; But &s;till it was a promi&s;e, and &s;hall be faithfully di&s;charged. &mdash; Here then in this pocket|book are notes for that &s;um.
<STAGE>[Mi&s;s RIVERS <HI>&s;hews an unwillingne&s;s to receive the pocket-book.</HI>]</STAGE> &mdash; Take it &mdash; but never &s;ee me more. &mdash; Bani&s;h my name eter|nally from your remembrance;&mdash;and when a little time &s;hall remove me from a world, which your conduct has rendered in&s;upportable, boa&s;t an additional title, my dear, to your hu&s;band's re|gard, by having &s;horten'd the life of your mi|&s;erable father. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
<STAGE><PB N="67" REF="73">
<HI>Enter</HI> SALLY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SALLY.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, Madam, is he gone?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>How could I be &s;uch a mon&s;ter &mdash; &s;uch an unnatural mon&s;ter as ever to think of leaving him. &mdash; But come, Sally, let us go into the hou&s;e.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SALLY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go into the hou&s;e, Madam! &mdash; Why are'nt we to go off with Sir Harry? &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>This in&s;en&s;ible creature has been my confident too! &mdash; O I &s;hall eternally dete&s;t my&s;elf. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sir HARRY <HI>and</HI> CECIL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg a thou&s;and pardons, my dear Mi&s;s Rivers, for detaining you. &mdash; An unfore&s;een accident prevented me from being punctual, &mdash; but the carriage is now ready, and a few hours will whirl us to the &s;ummit of felicity. &mdash; My cou&s;in Cecil is kindly here to a&s;&s;i&s;t us &mdash; and &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Harry, I can never for&s;ake my father. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>By &s;ome accident he di&s;covered our de&s;ign, and came to this &s;pot, while I was trembling with expectation of your appearance. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, my dear creature? &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="68" REF="74">
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here, in a melancholy but re&s;olute voice, he expatiated on the infamy of my intended &s;light, and mentioned my want of affection for him in terms that pierc'd my very &s;oul: &mdash; Having done this, he took an abrupt leave, and, &s;corning to detain me by force, for&s;ook me to the cour&s;e of my own inclinations.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, my angel, and &s;ince he has left you to follow your own inclinations, you will not, &s;urely, he&s;itate to &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Harry, unloo&s;e my hand; &mdash; the univer&s;e wou'd'nt bribe me now to go off with you. &mdash; O, Sir Harry! if you regarded your own peace you wou'd cea&s;e this importunity; &mdash; for is it po&s;&s;ible that a woman can make a valuable wife, who has prov'd an unnatural daughter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>But con&s;ider your own happine&s;s, my dear Mi&s;s Rivers &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>My own happine&s;s, Sir Harry! &mdash; What a wretch mu&s;t the woman be, who can dream of happine&s;s while &s;he wounds the bo&s;om of a father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a noble girl! &mdash; I &s;hall love her my&s;elf for her &s;en&s;e and her goodne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SALLY, <HI>a&s;ide, to</HI> Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>She won't con&s;ent, I know, Sir Harry, &mdash; &s;o, if the coach is at hand, it will be the be&s;t way to carry her off directly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, my dear Mi&s;s Rivers, there is no hope.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="69" REF="75">
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Harry, I mu&s;t not hear you. &mdash; This parting is a kind of death &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Part, Madam! &mdash; by all that's gracious we mu&s;t not part. &mdash; My whole &s;oul is unalterably fix'd upon you, &mdash; and &s;ince &mdash; neither tender|ne&s;s for your&s;elf, nor affection for me, per&s;uade you to the only mea&s;ure which can promote our mu|tual felicity, you mu&s;t forgive the de&s;pair that forces you from hence, and commits a momenta|ry di&s;re&s;pect to avoid a la&s;ting unhappine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hear me, Sir Harry &mdash; I conjure you hear me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me but remove you from this place, Madam, and I'll hear every thing. &mdash; Cecil, a&s;&s;i&s;t me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, Mr. Cecil, I rely upon your honour to &s;ave and protect me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>And it &s;hall, Madam. &mdash; For &s;hame kin&s;man, unhand the Lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Unhand her, what do you mean Cecil?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do I mean, I mean to protect the Lady. &mdash; What &s;hould a man of honour mean?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS, <HI>breaking from</HI> Sir Harry.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Mr. Cecil don't let him follow me</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[She runs off.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="70" REF="76">
<SPEAKER>SALLY, <HI>following.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I'll give her warning this moment, that's the &s;hort and the long of it.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Cecil, this is no time for tri&s;ling, &mdash; Did'nt you come here to a&s;&s;i&s;t me in carrying the Lady off?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>With her own inclinations, kin&s;man; &mdash; but as they are now on the other &s;ide of the que&s;tion, &s;o am I too. &mdash; You mu&s;t not follow her Sir Harry &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds! but I will!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds! but you &s;han't. &mdash; Look'ye, Harry, I came here to a&s;&s;i&s;t the purpo&s;es of a man of honour, not to abet the violence of a ru&s;&s;ian; &mdash; your friends of the world, your fa&s;hionable friends, may, if they plea&s;e, &s;upport one another's vices, but I am a friend only to the virtues of a man; and where I &s;incerely e&s;teem him, I always endea|vour to make him hone&s;t in &s;pite of his teeth.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>An injury like this! &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Harry! &mdash; Harry! &mdash; don't advance: &mdash; I am not to be terrified, you know, from the &s;upport of what is ju&s;t; &mdash; and, though you may think it very brave to &s;ight in the defence of a bad action, it will do but little credit either to your under&s;tanding or your humanity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Cecil, there's no an&s;wering that. &mdash; Your Ju&s;tice and your genero&s;ity overpower me; &mdash;
<PB N="71" REF="77">You have re&s;tored me to my&s;elf. &mdash; It was mean, it was unmanly, it was infamous to think of u&s;ing force. &mdash; But I was di&s;tracted; &mdash; nay, I am di&s;|tracted now, and mu&s;t entirely rely upon your a&s;&s;i&s;tance to recover her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>As far as I can act with hone&s;ty, Harry, you may depend upon me; &mdash; but let me have no more violence, I beg of you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't mention it, Cecil, &mdash; I am heartily a&s;ham'd &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I am heartily glad of it. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray let us go to my hou&s;e and con&s;ult a little. &mdash; What a contemptible figure do I make! &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, pretty well, I think; but to be le&s;s &s;o, put up your &s;word, Harry &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>She never can forgive me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>If &s;he does, &s;he will &s;carcely de&s;erve to be forgiven her&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't, Cecil; 'tis ungenerous to be &s;o hard upon me. &mdash; I own my faults, and you &s;hould encourage me, for every coxcomb has not &s;o much mode&s;ty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, &s;o I will, Harry; for mode&s;ty, I &s;ee, as yet, &s;its upon you but very aukwardly.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.]</STAGE>
<TRAILER><HI>End of the fourth</HI> ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="act">
<PB N="72" REF="78">
<HEAD>ACT V.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE <HI>an Apartment at</HI> Lady BETTY's.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RIVERS <HI>and</HI> SIDNEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I AM deeply &s;en&s;ible of Mi&s;s Rivers's very great merit, Sir; &mdash; but &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>But what, Sir, &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hear me with temper, I be&s;eech you, Colonel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hear you with temper: &mdash; I don't know whe|ther I &s;hall be able to hear you with temper; &mdash; but go on, Sir. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Rivers, independent of her very affluent fortune, Colonel, has beauty and merit which would make her alliance a very great honour to the fir&s;t family in the kingdom &mdash; But, notwith|&s;tanding my admiration of her beauty, and my reverence for her merit, I find it utterly impo&s;&s;ible to pro&s;it either by her goodne&s;s, or your genero&s;ity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>How is all this, Sir! do you decline a mar|riage with my daughter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>A marriage with Mi&s;s Rivers, Sir, was once the object of my highe&s;t ambition, and, had I been honoured with her hand, I &s;hould have &s;tudied to &s;hew my &s;en&s;ibility of a ble&s;&s;ing &s;o invaluble; &mdash; but, at that time, I did not &s;up|po&s;e
<PB N="73" REF="79">my happine&s;s to be incompatible with her's. &mdash; I am now convinced that is &s;o, and it becomes me much better to give up my own hopes, than to offer the &s;malle&s;t violence to her inclinations.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Death and hell, Sir! &mdash; what do you mean by this behaviour? &mdash; Shall I prefer your alliance to any man's in England? &mdash; Shall my daughter even expre&s;s a readine&s;s to marry you? &mdash; and &s;hall you, after this, in&s;olently tell me you don't choo&s;e to accept her? &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Colonel, you totally mi&s;conceive my mo|tive, &mdash; and, I am &s;ure, upon reflexion, you will rather approve than condemn it &mdash; A man of common humanity, Sir, in a treaty of marriage, &s;hould con&s;ult the lady's wi&s;hes as well as his own, and, if he can't make her happy, he will &s;corn to make her mi&s;erable.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Scorn to make her mi&s;erable! &mdash; why the fel|low's mad, I believe &mdash; Does'nt the girl ab&s;olute|ly con&s;ent to have you? &mdash; Would you have her drag you to the altar by force? &mdash; Would you have her fall at your feet, and beg of you, with tears, to pity one of the fine&s;t women, with one of the be&s;t fortunes, in England?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your vehemence, Sir, prevents you from con|&s;idering this matter in a proper light. &mdash; Mi&s;s Rivers is &s;ufficiently unhappy in lo&s;ing the man of her heart, but her di&s;tre&s;s mu&s;t be greatly ag|gravated, if, in the moment &s;he is mo&s;t keenly &s;en&s;ible of this lo&s;s, &s;he is compelled to marry an|other. &mdash; Be&s;ides, Colonel, I mu&s;t have my &s;eel|ings
<PB N="74" REF="80">too. &mdash; There is &s;omething &s;hocking in a union with a woman who&s;e affections we know to be alienated; and 'tis difficult to &s;ay which is mo&s;t entitled to contempt, he that &s;toops to accept of a pre-engaged mind, or he that puts up with a pro&s;tituted per&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mighty well, Sir, &mdash; mighty well; but let me tell you, Mr. Sidney, &mdash; that under this &s;pecious appearance of genero&s;ity I can ea&s;ily &s;ee your your motive for this refu&s;al of my daughter, &mdash; let me tell you I can ea&s;ily &s;ee your motive, Sir, &mdash; and, let me tell you, that the per&s;on who is in po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of your affections &s;hall no longer find an a&s;ylum in this hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Colonel, if I had not been always accu&s;tomed to re&s;pect you, &mdash; and if I did not even con&s;i|der this in&s;ult as a kind of compliment, I don't know how I &s;hould put up with it: as to your in&s;inuation, you mu&s;t be more explicit before I can under&s;tand you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Marchmont, &mdash; Sir. &mdash; Do you under&s;tand me now, Sir? If Mi&s;s Marchmont had not been in the ca&s;e my daughter had not received this in|&s;ult. &mdash; Sir Harry was right; and had not I been ridiculou&s;ly be&s;otted with your hypocritical plau|&s;ibility I might have &s;een it &s;ooner, but your cou|&s;in &s;hall know of your behaviour, and then, Sir, you &s;hall an&s;wer me as a man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Marchmont, Colonel, is greatly above this illiberal reflexion; as for my&s;elf, I &s;hall be always ready to ju&s;tify an action which I know to
<PB N="75" REF="81">be right, though I &s;hould be &s;orry ever to meet you but in the character of a friend.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS, </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[alone.]</STAGE>
<P>Well! &mdash; well! &mdash; well! &mdash; but it doesn't &s;ig|nify, &mdash; it doesn't &s;ignify, &mdash; it doesn't &s;ignify. &mdash; I won't put my&s;elf in a pa&s;&s;ion about it. I won't put my&s;elf in a pa&s;&s;ion about it. I'll tear the fel|low piece-meal. &mdash; Zounds! I don't know what I'll do.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.]</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Mrs HARLEY</HI> and <HI>CECIL.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why this is better and better.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a violent pa&s;&s;ion he's in.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is the very thing I could wi&s;h &mdash; 'twill ad|vance a principal part of our project rarely &mdash; well is'nt Sidney a noble young fellow, and does'nt he richly de&s;erve the regard which my poor little girl entertains for him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why really I think he does &mdash; but how &s;ecret|ly my Lady Sentimental carried matters &mdash; O I always &s;aid that your grave, reflecting, moralizing dam&s;els &mdash; were a thou&s;and times more &s;u&s;cept|ible of tender impre&s;&s;ions than tho&s;e lively open hearted girls who talk away at random, and &s;eem ready to run off with every man that happens to fall into their company.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know, widow, but there may be &s;ome truth in this, you &s;ee at lea&s;t I have &s;uch a good opinion of a madcap, that you are the fir&s;t per|&s;on I have made acquainted with the &s;ecret.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="76" REF="82">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well and hav'nt I returned the compliment by letting you into my de&s;ign about Lady Betty and Lord Winworth?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a ridiculous bu&s;tle is there here about de|licacy and &s;tuff&mdash;your people of refin'd &s;entiments are the mo&s;t trouble&s;ome creatures in the world to deal with, and their friends mu&s;t even commit a violence upon their nicety before they can con|de&s;cend to &s;tudy their own happine&s;s: &mdash; But have you done as we concerted?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I have pretended to Lady Betty that my Lord de&s;ires to &s;peak with her privately on bu&s;i|ne&s;s of the utmo&s;t importance; and I have told his Lord&s;hip that &s;he wants to &s;ee him, to di&s;clo&s;e a &s;ecret that mu&s;t intirely break off the intended marriage with Mi&s;s Marchmont.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>What an aukward figure they mu&s;t make, each imagining that the other has de&s;ired the inter|view &mdash; and expecting every moment to be told &s;omething of con&s;equence &mdash; but you have not given either the lea&s;t hint of Horten&s;ia's &s;ecret inclination for Sidney?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>How could you po&s;&s;ibly &s;uppo&s;e &s;uch a thing?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, to your part of the bu&s;ine&s;s then, while I find out the Colonel and try what I can do with him for my rattle-pated Sir Harry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>O never doubt my a&s;&s;iduity in an affair of this nature.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.]</STAGE>
<STAGE><PB N="77" REF="83">
<HI>Enter</HI> Lady BETTY, <HI>in another Apartment.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>What can he want with me I wonder?&mdash;Speak with me again in private, and upon bu&s;ine&s;s of the utmo&s;t importance! he has &s;poken &s;ufficient|ly to me already upon his bu&s;ine&s;s of importance to make me mi&s;erable for ever. &mdash; But the fault is my own, and I have nobody to blame but my|&s;elf. &mdash; Ble&s;s me here he is.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> WINWORTH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam your mo&s;t devoted, I come in obedi|ence to your commands to &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>My commands my Lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Madam, your me&s;&s;age has alarm'd me prodigiou&s;ly &mdash; and you cannot wonder if I am a little impatient for an explanation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Impatient for an explanation, my Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Madam, the affair is of the neare&s;t con|cern to my happine&s;s, and the &s;ooner you honour me with &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Honour you, with what my Lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Lady Betty this re&s;erve is unkind, e&s;pecially as you know how unea&s;y I mu&s;t be till I hear from your&s;elf&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Really my Lord I am quite a&s;toni&s;hed &mdash; un|ea&s;y till you hear from my&s;elf &mdash; impatient for an explanation &mdash; I beg your Lord&s;hip will tell me what is the meaning of all this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="78" REF="84">
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Surely, Madam, you cannot &s;o &s;uddenly change your kind intentions &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ledy BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>My kind intentions, my Lord!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>I would not, Madam, be too pre&s;uming, but, as I know your Lady&s;hip's goodne&s;s, I flatter my|&s;elf that &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your Lord&s;hip is all a my&s;tery&mdash;I beg you will &s;peak out &mdash; for upon my word I don't under|&s;tand the&s;e half &s;entences. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Madam, Mrs. Harley has told me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY, </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[with eagerne&s;s.]</STAGE>
<P>What has &s;he told you, my Lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>She has told me of the &s;ecret, Madam, which you have to di&s;clo&s;e, that mu&s;t entirely break off my marriage with Mi&s;s Marchmont.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Has &s;he then betrayed my weakne&s;s? &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, I hope you won't think your generous intentions in my favour a weakne&s;s, for be a&s;&s;ur'd that the &s;tudy of my whole life &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I did not think that Mrs. Harley could be ca|pable of &s;uch an action; &mdash; but &s;ince &s;he has told you of the only circum&s;tance which I ever wi&s;h'd to be conceal'd, I cannot deny my partiality for your Lord&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="79" REF="85">
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>This &s;ecret was tru&s;ted with her, and her alone; but though &s;he has ungenerou&s;ly di&s;cover'd it, her end will &s;till be di&s;appointed. I acknowledge that I prize your Lord&s;hip above all the world; &mdash; but even to obtain you I will not be guilty of a ba&s;ene&s;s, nor promote my own happine&s;s by any act of inju&s;tice to Mi&s;s Marchmont.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am the mo&s;t unfortunate man in the world; &mdash; and does your Lady&s;hip really honour me with any degree of a tender partiality?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>This que&s;tion is needle&s;s, my Lord, after what Mrs. Harley has acquainted you with.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mrs. Harley, Madam, has not acquainted me with particulars of any nature &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>No!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>No. &mdash; And happy as this di&s;covery would have made me at any other time, it now di&s;tre&s;&s;es me be|yond expre&s;&s;ion, &s;ince the engagements I have ju&s;t enter'd into with Mi&s;s Marchmont put it wholly out of my power to receive any benefit from the knowledge of your &s;entiments. &mdash; O, Lady Betty, had you been generou&s;ly candid when I &s;olicited the ble&s;&s;ing of your hand, how much had I been indebted to your goodne&s;s; but now, think what my &s;ituation is, when, in the moment I am &s;en&s;ible of your regard, I mu&s;t give you up for ever.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> CECIL <HI>and</HI> Mrs. HARLEY <HI>from oppo&s;ite Places.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY, </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[repeating ludicrou&s;ly.]</STAGE>
<Q>Who can behold &s;uch beauty and be &s;ilent!</Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="80" REF="86">
<SPEAKER>CECIL, </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[in the &s;ame accent.]</STAGE>
<Q>De&s;ire fir&s;t taught us words. &mdash;</Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<Q>Man, when created, wander'd up and down.</Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<Q>Forlorn and &s;ilent as his va&s;&s;al bea&s;ts;</Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<Q>But when a heav'n-born maid like you ap|pear'd,</Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<Q>Strange plea&s;ure fill'd his eyes, and &s;eiz'd his heart,</Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<Q>Unloos'd his tongue.</Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<Q>And his fir&s;t talk was love.</Q>
<STAGE>[<HI>Both,</HI> ha! ha! ha!]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, Mr. Cecil, what is the meaning of this whim&s;ical behaviour?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>The nature of this conduct, Mrs. Harley, bears too &s;trong a re&s;emblance to a late di&s;ingenuity, for me to wonder at.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>What di&s;ingenuity, my dear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, pray, Madam, what &s;ecret had I to di&s;clo&s;e to his Lord&s;hip?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>The &s;ecret which you have di&s;clos'd, my dear,&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[court&s;eying.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg, my Lord, that we may'nt interrupt your heroics, <Q>when, in the moment you are &s;en&s;ible
<PB N="81" REF="87">of her regard, &mdash; you mu&s;t give her up for ever.</Q> &mdash; A very moving &s;peech, Mrs. Harley, &mdash;I am &s;ure it almo&s;t makes me cry to repeat it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Cecil, li&s;tening is &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>What are we going to have a quarrel? &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, yes! your lover is a mere nobody without a little blood&s;hed, two or three duels give a won|derful addition to his character.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, what is the meaning of all this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;hall know in a moment, Madam, &mdash; &s;o walk in, good people, &mdash; walk in, and &s;ee the mo&s;t &s;urpri&s;ing pair of true lovers, who have too much &s;en&s;e to be wi&s;e, and too much delicacy to be happy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Walk in, &mdash; walk in.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RIVERS, Mi&s;s RIVERS, Mi&s;s MARCH|MONT, Sir HARRY, <HI>and</HI> SIDNEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, Emmy! is this behaving like a friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, and like a true friend, as you &s;hall &s;ee pre&s;ently. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord, I give you joy, joy heartily. &mdash; We have been po&s;ted for &s;ome time under the direc|tion of Mar&s;hal Cecil, and General Harley, in the next room, who have acquainted us with every
<PB N="82" REF="88">thing; and I feel the &s;incere&s;t &s;atisfaction to think the perplexities of to-day have &s;o fortunate a con|clu&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>The perplexities of to-day are not yet con|cluded, Colonel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, Lady Betty, why wou'dn't you tru&s;t me with your &s;ecret? I have been the innocent cau&s;e of great unea&s;ine&s;s to you, and yet my conduct en|tirely proceeded from the greatne&s;s of my affection.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know it, my dear, &mdash; I know it well; &mdash; but were you to give up Lord Winworth this mo|ment &mdash; be a&s;&s;ured that I wou'dn't accept of any &s;acrifice made at the expence of your happine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>At the Expence of her happine&s;s! &mdash; O, is that all? &mdash; Come here ma&s;ter Sober&s;ides [<HI>to</HI> Sidney] and come here, Madam Gravity [<HI>to</HI> Mi&s;s March|mont] come here, I &s;ay, &mdash; I &s;uppo&s;e, my Lord, I &s;uppo&s;e, Lady Betty, that you already know from what very manly motives&mdash;Sidney, here, has declined the marriage with Mi&s;s Rivers?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do, and though I lament the impo&s;&s;ibility of a relation to the Colonel's family, I cannot but ad|mire his behaviour on that occa&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I think it extremely generous.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Cecil, &s;tand by a little, you &s;han't have the whole management of this di&s;covery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did you ever &s;ee &s;uch a woman!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="83" REF="89">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, my Lord and Lady Betty, &s;ince we have agreed thus far, you mu&s;t know that Mr. Sidney's behaviour has produced more good con&s;equences than you can imagine. &mdash; In the fir&s;t place it has enabled Colonel Rivers, without a breach of his word, &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>To give his daughter to my fooli&s;h kin&s;man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>You wont hold your tongue.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>And, in the next place, it has enabled Mr. Sidney &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>To marry Mi&s;s Marchmont.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, &s;he will have the la&s;t word. &mdash; For it &s;eems that between the&s;e two turtles there has long &s;ub|&s;i&s;ted &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>A very tender affection, &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>The devil's in her tongue, &mdash; &s;he has the &s;peed of me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>What an unexpected felicity?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am all amazement!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, my dear &s;i&s;ter,&mdash;no wondering about it, &mdash; at a more convenient time you &s;hall know particulars; for the pre&s;ent let me tell you, that now I am cool, and that matters have been pro|perly
<PB N="84" REF="90">explain'd to me, I am not only &s;atisfied but charm'd with Mr. Sidney's behaviour, though it has prevented the fir&s;t wi&s;h of my heart; and I hope that his Lord&s;hip and you, by con&s;ent|ing to his marriage with Mi&s;s Marchmont, will im|mediately remove every impediment in the way of your own happine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>If my own happine&s;s was not to be promoted by &s;uch a &s;tep, I &s;hould in&s;tantly give my con&s;ent; &mdash; and therefore, my dear Mi&s;s Marchmont, if I have Lady Betty's approbation, and your own con|currence, I here be&s;tow this hand upon as de&s;erv|ing a young man as any in the univer&s;e. &mdash; This is the only attonement I can make for the unea&s;i|ne&s;s I have given you, and if your happine&s;s is any way proportion'd to your merit, I need not wi&s;h you a greater &s;hare of felicity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>What &s;hall I &s;ay, my Lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Say nothing, Charles, for if you only knew how exqui&s;ite a &s;atisfaction I receive on this occa&s;ion, you would rather envy my feelings than think your&s;elf under an obligation; &mdash; and now, my dear Lady Betty, if I might pre&s;ume &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>That I may not be cen&s;ur'd any longer, I here declare my hand your Lord&s;hip's whenever you think proper to demand it; for I am now con|vinc'd the greate&s;t proof which a woman can give of her own worth, is to entertain an affection for a man of honour and under&s;tanding.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>This goodne&s;s, Madam, is too great for ac|knowledgment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="85" REF="91">
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>And now, my dear Theodora, let me con|gratulate with you: I rejoice that your inclinations are con&s;ulted in the mo&s;t important circum&s;tance of your life, and I am &s;ure Sir Harry will not be wanting in gratitude for the partiality which you have &s;hewn in his favour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Madam, you oblige me infinitely.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>And as for me, Lady Betty, it is &s;o much my inclination to de&s;erve the partiality with which Mi&s;s Rivers has honour'd me, as well as to repay the goodne&s;s of her family, that I &s;hall have little merit in my gratitude to either; I have been wild, I have been incon&s;iderate, but I hope I never was de&s;picable; and I flatter my&s;elf I &s;han't be wanting in acknowledgment only to tho&s;e, who have laid me under the greate&s;t of all obligations.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Harry, &s;ay no more: &mdash; My girl's repen|tance has been &s;o noble, your Cou&s;in Cecil's be|haviour has been &s;o generous, and I believe you, after all, to be a man of &s;uch principle; &mdash; that next to Sidney I don't know who I &s;hou'd prefer to you for a &s;on-in-law. &mdash; But you mu&s;t think a little for the future, and remember that it is a poor excu&s;e for playing the fool, to be po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ed of a good under&s;tanding.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, there &s;eems but one thing remaining undone: &mdash; I ju&s;t now took the liberty of exer|ci&s;ing a father's right over Mi&s;s Marchmont, by di&s;po&s;ing of her hand, 'tis now nece&s;&s;ary for me&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="86" REF="92">
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold, my Lord &mdash; I gue&s;s what you are about, but you &s;han't monopolize genero&s;ity I a&s;&s;ure you: &mdash; I have a right to &s;hew my friend&s;hip as well as your Lord&s;hip; &s;o, after your kin&s;man's marriage, whatever you have a mind to do for him &s;hall be equalled, on my part, for Mi&s;s Marchmont; guinea for guinea, as far as you will, and let's &s;ee who tires fir&s;t in going through with it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>A noble challange, and I accept it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady BETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, there's no bearing this &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s MARCHMONT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Speak to them, Mr. Sidney, for I cannot &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIDNEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h I had words to declare my &s;en&s;e of this goodne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I did'nt look upon my&s;elf as a very pitiful fellow; but I am &s;trangely &s;unk in my own opi|nion &s;ince I have been a witne&s;s of this tran&s;action.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why what the devil is there in all this to won|der at? People of fortune often throw away thou&s;ands at the hazard table to make them&s;elves mi&s;erable, and nobody ever accu&s;es them of ge|nero&s;ity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Cecil is perfectly right, and he is the be&s;t manager of a fortune who is mo&s;t attentive to the wants of the de&s;erving.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="87" REF="93">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why now all is as it &s;hou'd be &mdash; all is as it &s;hou'd be &mdash; this is the triumph of good &s;en&s;e over delicacy. &mdash; I could cry for downright joy: &mdash; I wonder what ails me &mdash; this is all my doing!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, &mdash; part of it is mine, &mdash; and I think it ex|tremely happy for your people of refin'd &s;enti|ments to have friends with a little common under|&s;tanding.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Si&s;ter, I always thought you a woman of &s;en&s;e.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs HARLEY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;he has been a long time intimate with me you know.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CECIL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well &s;aid, &s;auce-box.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>If this &s;tory was to be repre&s;ented on the &s;tage the poet would think it his duty to puni&s;h me for life, becau&s;e I was once culpable.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WINWORTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>That wou'd be very wrong. The &s;tage &s;hou'd be a &s;chool of morality; and the noble&s;t of all le&s;&s;ons is the forgivene&s;s of injuries.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RIVERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, my Lord. &mdash; But the principal moral to be drawn from the tran&s;actions of to-day is, that tho&s;e who generou&s;ly labour for the happine&s;s of others, will, &s;ooner or later, arrive at happine&s;s them&s;elves.</P>
</SP>
</DIV2>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
</DIV1>
